How does anxiety feel?
Spoiler: It's not just "worrying a lot" ⚠️

Anxiety is as if your body and mind were put in alarm mode ... although there is no real danger 

In the head:
• Thoughts that go in loop, as if you couldn't turn them off 
• Fear of the future or things that have not even happened 
• It is hard for you to concentrate because your mind is in a thousand places at the same time ️

In the body:
• Chest oppression or feeling that you can't breathe well 
• The heart accelerates without reason ❤️‍
• You can sweat, tremble or feel nausea 

In emotions:
• That feeling of “something is wrong”, even if you don't know what ⚡
• You are more irritable or wanting to cry without apparent reason 

What can you do if it happens to you?
• For a moment and breathe: 4 seconds onhalas, 4 endures, 4 exhales ‍♀️
• Tell someone how you feel ️
• And most importantly: asking for help does not make you weak, it makes you brave ✨

Many people suffer from a type of anxiety that {{EMAIL}}. Just at the moment when the body and mind should prepare for rest they are assaulted by a pressing state of anxiety that does not allow them to loosen. 

Overwhelming thoughts, concern
generalized, feeling of uneasiness, state of restlessness, fears, doubts and hesitations are some of the anxiety symptoms that, if they fly over the night, prevent the sleep from reconciling.

Tips for controlling anxiety at night:

Performing physical exercise: doing physical activity is beneficial for physical, and mental health. When exercising, we release serotonin and endorphins, which help us feel better and reduce stress by promoting the decrease in cortisol in the body.

Take care of food: it is advisable to make light dinners and avoid very abundant meals during the night.

Avoid drinking with caffeine or exciting from mid -afternoon.

Maintain a fixed schedule to sleep.

Practice relaxation techniques: they help fight insomnia and overcome anxiety and stress.

Avoid using electronic devices 30 minutes before sleeping: these devices stimulate the mind and hinder sleep.

Establish a sleep routine that helps rest: a hot bath with relaxing salts, quiet music, reading are some actions that can help.

Did you know that anxiety and stress can be manifested in this way? 

Anxiety and stress are very difficult to handle, and sometimes they manifest unexpectedly, such as sleeping much more than normal.

Excess sleep during an episode of stress and anxiety may be due to:
1. Emotional exhaustion
2. Active parasympathetic nervous system 
3. High stress hormones (cortisol, adrenaline)
4. Defense mechanisms
5. Neurotransmitters imbalance (serotonin, dopamine)
6. Physical fatigue
7. Avoidance (avoid stressful situations)
8. Emotional regulation

But it's not just tiredness. Anxiety and stress can affect your daily life, your relationships and your well -being in general. They can make you feel without energy and without wanting to do anything.

If you feel like this, talk to someone of trust, seek professional support and remember that there are ways to feel better.

Many people look for how to know if I have anxiety, physical symptoms of daily anxiety, how to identify a silent anxiety attack or why I feel oppression in the chest for no apparent reason. But anxiety is not always seen from the outside. Sometimes, he suffers in silence, every day.

If you ever looked for how to recognize physical anxiety signs, how to calm an accelerated heart, how to sleep better when you have anxiety or how to stop repetitive negative thoughts, you know how difficult it is.

Each little achievement counts: sleep a little better, soothe a thought, survive another day. Anxiety makes you question everything. Did I say it well? Will it have bothered? What if I'm wrong? What if everything goes wrong? Living like this tires the soul. The spontaneity, peace, the ability to enjoy the moment steals. And the worst part is that you do it in silence, without anyone noticing it, appearing that everything is fine while inside your mind does not stop for a second. You would like to turn it off, rest, feel safe again, but you don't know how.

You are not alone in this silent battle. Every day you choose not to give up, even if it's just breathing a little deeper, you are healing. Not everything has to be resolved today. Not everything depends on you. You deserve to live in peace, you deserve to trust you, you deserve to heal without guilt or hurry. Your anxiety does not define your story. It's just a part of her.

Saying “just breathing” to someone who is in anxiety crisis may seem an attempt to help, but in practice it only gets worse. Because those in crisis cannot control the body with willpower. The chest squeezes, the air does not seem to come right, thoughts accelerate, the body trembles. The person knows they need to breathe. The problem is that she feels she can't.

Anxiety in crisis is not resolved with ready sentences. What helps most at this moment is not a quick tip is presence, welcome and safety. Sometimes just hearing a “I'm here with you, let's go through it together” already makes all the difference.

It is important to understand that no one chooses to have a crisis. And that those who are living it needs support, not judgment or pressure. Welcoming with empathy is always the best way.

A panic attack is a feeling of sudden and intense anxiety.
Panic attacks can also have physical symptoms:

shaking, 
feeling disorientated, 
nausea, 
rapid, irregular heartbeats, 
dry mouth, 
breathlessness, 
sweating, 
dizziness.
The symptoms of a panic attack are not dangerous, but can be very frightening.

The person might feel like having a heart attack, collapsing or even dying.

Most panic attacks last somewhere from 5 minutes to half an hour.

Important:
Recognize a panic attack, 
Sit next to the person and talk to the person in a calm voice. 
Say motivating words and take the person's hand or stroke the shoulder, for example.

Anxiety can generate stress, but there is also a positive side in feeling a bit nervous. Not only can it help you give up to the fullest, but it can also trigger the release of brain chemicals that help you motivate you to pursue your goals.

We often listen about the negative aspects of anxiety, so it can be a bit surprising to know that feeling anxious or nervous can be {{EMAIL}}. After all, anxiety is a feeling that is often characterized by intense fear, concern and apprehension.

Many people with anxiety describe it as a feeling of nervousness and fear that, at best, can distract it and, in the worst, consume everything. Anxiety is generally experienced at many levels, affecting emotions, causing uncomfortable physical sensations and contributing to negative thoughts.

Anxiety can be informative
Anxiety can only be the warning signal you need to become aware of your current situation and make some necessary changes in your life. Recurring concern and nervousness can be an indication that some areas of your life are out of place and need adjustments.

Anxiety can help you motivate you
Instead of always considering an obstacle, anxiety can actually help you feel more motivated and prepared when you face challenges. Anxiety can help trigger the release of dopamine, a cerebral chemical that can help people feel more motivated to pursue their goals. Feeling a little anxious for something can help you study more, practice more and be more prepared to face the situation.

And both are equally horrible to experience. 

When we have an anxiety attack it tends to mean our stress response has reached a point of overload, often triggered by prolonged worry or anticipation of a stressful event. 

 When we have a panic attack it tends to tell us our body's "fight or flight" system has been activated intensely and suddenly, often without an obvious immediate threat.

 The primary differences included:
 
Anxiety attacks build gradually, with a less intense peak.
Panic attacks come on abruptly, with a sudden and overwhelming surge of fear.
 
Anxiety attacks can last for extended periods, even hours.
Panic attacks typically peak within minutes and subside relatively quickly.

Anxiety attacks are often linked to identifiable stressors or triggers.
Panic attacks can occur seemingly out of the blue, though underlying vulnerabilities may exist.

Anxiety attacks present with muscle tension, restlessness, and general unease.
Panic attacks show more extreme physical signs like chest pain, heart palpitations, and a sense of impending doom.

Anxiety attacks are often caused by prolonged stress, or anxiety disorders.
Panic attacks can be caused by panic disorder, or extreme stress, and sometimes medical conditions.

To Clarify 
Panic attacks are a recognised medical condition
 'Anxiety attack' is not, but describes real experiences of intense anxiety. Both can be just as debilitating and both require kindness and care.

Do you dance with your anxiety?

Anxiety is a physiological response that comes to let us know that something is not right. No one dies from an anxiety attack, but it is a very unpleasant feeling and that is why we usually try to feel it. 

The issue is that the more we avoid feeling the most monstrous anxiety becomes (as in the video) and further we are going to have a good time dancing with it. Besides that the more we avoid it, the more we have to know why it has come and what it needs from us. 

To learn how to dance so with anxiety you can help you:

-Asaber what anxiety is and how is its operation 
-In anxiety is a set of physiological sensations that will sooner or later decrease in intensity
-Bust support, express your emotions with other people who take care of you
-Tera yourself well while you feel it, not demanding to be a superhero 
-To techniques that can help you with symptoms while you learn little by little to let it feel
-Secuchar yourself, understand and meet you to see what need of yours does not cover anxiety and see if you can do something to cover it
-Trabar in a deeper way that anxiety comes from trauma

Anxiety feeds off uncertainty—and that makes sense. Not knowing what’s coming can feel overwhelming, even threatening.
ㅤ
But here’s something most of us never learn: it’s not always the uncertainty itself that wrecks us. It’s the way we try to fight it—chasing answers, control, and guarantees we may never get.
ㅤ
You don’t need certainty to take the next step. You need courage to move forward anyway.
ㅤ
The more you can sit with “I don’t know,” the more grounded you’ll feel—even when life’s up in the air. And, let’s be honest, isn’t it always?
ㅤ
Drop a  in the comments if you’re learning to live with the unknown, one day at a time.
ㅤ

OCD (obsessive-compulsive disorder) on the left: healthy brain. On the right: for OCD - excessive activity in frontal areas. Why: The brain seems to be "stuck" on anxious thoughts.                  Anxiety (anxiety) on the left: normal activity. On the right: the brain is in constant readiness - many red zones. Why: Hyperactification of the almond -shaped body, which is responsible for fear.                                   Bipolar Disorder (bipolar disorder) on the left: balanced condition. On the right: strong changes- alternation of hypo- and hyperactive zones. Why: The brain varies between depression and mania.                           ADHD (SDVG) on the left: stable activity. On the right: excessive activation in motor and frontal areas. Why: The brain is constantly looking for an stimulus, it is difficult to concentrate.                PTSD (post -traumatic stress disorder) left: healthy balance. Case: Increased activity in memory and fear. Why: The brain lives in the "danger now" mode.  Eating Disorder (anorexia/bulimia) on the left: uniform brain function. On the right: the brain is "stopped" on control of body, nutrition, guilt. Why: The dopamine system has been changed. Schizphrenia (schizophrenia) on the left: normal structure. Case: chaotic activity and "breaks" in communication between zones. Why: The work of neurotrans and dopamine is impaired. Panic Disorder (panic disorder) on the left: stable activity. On the right: the brain is "ignited" in stress - active areas of fear. Why: Exaggerated reaction to the internal signals of the body. BORDERLINE PERSONALITY Disorder (border disorder) on the left: stable balance. On the right: high activity in emotional zones, instability. I'm sharing this not for sympathy from anyone, but to create awareness. I took this video of my hand shaking to show a very real, physical reaction my body had to someone I don't want near me. Someone I do not want in my life. This isn't dramatized. This isn't exaggerated. This is trauma and anxiety showing up in real time. The boundaries I created have not been {{EMAIL}}. It's not always loud. It's not always a dramatic scene. Sometimes it's your nervous system quietly screaming for safety while you're trying to hold yourself together. Respecting someone’s boundaries isn’t optional. It’s not something to negotiate or test. It's a basic requirement of being in someone's life—and I’ve made it clear that this person is not welcome in mine. To anyone else going through something similar—you're not alone. And your body, your reactions, your gut feelings—they are all valid.

Many people suffer from a type of anxiety that {{EMAIL}}. Just at the moment when the body and mind should prepare for rest they are assaulted by a pressing state of anxiety that does not allow them to loosen. 

Overwhelming thoughts, concern
generalized, feeling of uneasiness, state of restlessness, fears, doubts and hesitations are some of the anxiety symptoms that, if they fly over the night, prevent the sleep from reconciling.

Tips for controlling anxiety at night:

Performing physical exercise: doing physical activity is beneficial for physical, and mental health. When exercising, we release serotonin and endorphins, which help us feel better and reduce stress by promoting the decrease in cortisol in the body.

Take care of food: it is advisable to make light dinners and avoid very abundant meals during the night.

Avoid drinking with caffeine or exciting from mid -afternoon.

Maintain a fixed schedule to sleep.

Practice relaxation techniques: they help fight insomnia and overcome anxiety and stress.

Avoid using electronic devices 30 minutes before sleeping: these devices stimulate the mind and hinder sleep.

Establish a sleep routine that helps rest: a hot bath with relaxing salts, quiet music, reading are some actions that can help.

Depression is invisible, silent, but deeply real. They are not "stupid whims", they are not passenger thoughts that can be ignored or fighting only with willpower. It is a presence that insinuates itself even in the moments that, apparently, should be perfect. I was on the other side of the world, in my favorite country, in a place that I had always dreamed of living. I was surrounded by splendid people, sincere smiles, hugs who should have warmed my heart. I knew I had a house, a family ready to welcome me with open arms, a life that awaited me, full of opportunities and love. Yet despite all this, I felt empty. It was like walking in a wonderful landscape without being able to see its colors, like listening to sweet music without really perceiving its melody. Inside it was all off, as if something essential was missing, even when I rationally knew I didn't miss anything. Depression empties you slowly, convinces you that your happiness is unattainable, even when it is found around you. It makes you feel foreign even to your dreams, imprison you in a sadness that does not need reasons to exist. And for this reason it is so difficult to explain, so easy to misunderstand, so invisible in the eyes of others. But not for this less real. ️
It is my way, if strong.

5 signs that you could be suffering silent depression without realizing it:
	1. You laugh with everyone, but inside you feel a huge void.
	2. You are exhausted, although you sleep enough.
	3. You don't want to be alone, but people exhaust you.
	4. What made you happy before, now you don't care.
	5. You always say "I'm fine", even if it's not true.

Depression does not always notice, but that does not mean that you don't deserve help. You don't have to face it alone.

Depression doesn’t always look like sadness. During the day, you can be laughing, joking, and seeming fine. But when the night comes, it’s a different story. It’s when the silence gets loud, and you’re left lying awake, feeling numb and empty, as memories and thoughts you can’t escape play on repeat. The hardest part isn’t just the pain—it’s the loneliness of feeling like no one sees what you’re carrying. If this resonates, know you’re not alone, and it’s okay to reach out. You’re stronger than the thoughts trying to break you.  #depression #depressionhelp #night #memories #sadcore #sad

Cinematic Diaries #05 ‘Social Media’ 

Social media addiction is one of the greatest issues faced by society nowadays. The constant need to check the phone, the numerous hours spent scrolling endlessly through the abyss of social media apps, the level of concern revolving around the life of others than oneself.

As easy as social media has made life for us, it’s also equally as damaging. Many people with social media use it as a tool to compare themselves to others. Comparing themselves to a life they believe they will never achieve. A life that was never real in the first place. This feeling of worthlessness then leads to a depressed state and further comparison. The scrolling continues.

Social media was invented as a tool to connect us, but instead, it has further disconnected us. The constant need to text others in the presence of a loved one. The lack of productivity. The preference of virtual communication over face to face conversations. 

Social media can be useful in limited usage. But sadly, it will continue to lure users into its endless snare. 

Look around sometime, cherish what you have around you. Find the beauty around you than within a screen. Live a real life, not a fake one.

Free yourself from cell addiction ‍↔️✨ summary

1️⃣ limits the time you spend writing. Every time you do, you receive small doses of dopamine, which creates an addiction in your body, not only in your mind. Hurrying the phone and taking long breaks is key to breaking this cycle.

2️⃣ controls the impulses of looking at the mobile. When the body asks you dopamine, do not fall into temptation. Put your mobile away from you and focus on another activity. At first it will be difficult, but over time, your body will get used not to depend on those constant doses.

3️⃣ Avoid falling into the stress trap and continuous anger. If you get up with a bad mood, it is possible that your body is asking for cortisol, the stress hormone. Be aware of your emotions and break with those repetitive patterns.

4️⃣ Detail your body of these neurochemical substances. At first you will feel a kind of withdrawal syndrome, but little by little the body will get used to working without depending on those discharges of dopamine or cortisol.

5️⃣ Train your mind to take control. It is important that the mind dominates the body, not vice versa. With will and discipline, you can break those chemical addictions and take the reins of your actions and thoughts.

Body Dysmorphia explained 

Also known as BDD (body dysmorphic disorder) is a mental health condition where you become fixated with how your appearance

You may have body dysmorphic disorder if you worry a lot about how a specific part of your body looks and it affects your daily life

It can often look like nothing to most people but to you will seem massive. You can become fixated on what you perceive as imperfection and flaws and worry about how you can change them. This can bring around anxiety and lead to other mental health disorders.

The exact cause of body dysmorphic disorder is unclear. It’s been linked to genes, chemical changes in the brain and traumatic past experiences

Also, as females, the way society has such intense pressures on us to look a certain way - and this changes all the time to whatever is the latest beauty trend - but our bodies are NOT trends

This is something I work with a lot of women on in order to reframe their mindset to feel their best - as I always say, your mental health is just as important as your physical - and my coaching goes way beyond just a workout plans and some calories 

Please know you’re not alone in feeling this way and you can reach out for help, even talking about it can feel like a load lifted - a problem shared is a problem halved

Humans are deeply drawn to connection. Although connection is important, don't let temporary company become a permanent compromise. 

Here's the thing about loneliness: it's not just an "empty space." 

When you're lonely, you learn the difference between someone who adds to your life and someone who fills it up. If you ask me, those two things are totally different!

Sometimes loneliness creates the space for something genuine to emerge. 

The feeling of loneliness isn't always a problem to solve; it can be an opportunity for you to grow and take some time to actually sit with yourself, which not many people do. 

When you don't learn to choose yourself before waiting for someone to choose you, you're only relying on others to fill your void. 

It's got to start with you.

Loneliness can sometimes cloud judgment, making it tempting to seek comfort or validation from others even if they aren't the right people for us. 

When we connect with people out of loneliness, it can lead to one-sided or unfulfilling relationships, which often don’t support our well-being or growth.

Instead, take time to work on yourself, build your interests, and develop a stronger sense of self-worth. 

When you’re confident and comfortable on your own, you’re more likely to form genuine, healthy connections with people who truly add value to your life.

Social networks are manipulating you and that is why we are addicted. They succeed by making intermittent reinforcement. To release dopamine in your brain. If you want to avoid it. Listen to this. David Greenfield, an expert psychologist in technology addictions, explains how social networks use intermittent variable rewards, a powerful tactic used, for example, by swallowing coins, so that your brain releases dopamine, taking control of your acting and unfortunately, making you completely addicted. Big and guys are spending five, eight hours a day glued to the phone. And if you want to avoid it, the answer is easy. Understand the above and look for real dopamine. Look for the sun, get into cold water, exercise, do difficult things, spend time with your family, play with your son, connect with your friends, work hard for your goals. This problem is very serious. If you let the release of dopamine in your brain be generated by easy external factors, you can never develop your potential and do not want to be 80 years old and say what fuck I did with my life? Are you addicted to social networks? #Addiction #RRRSS #Pocoimportantes

Excessive use of social networks, also known as cyber -confidence or addiction to social networks, can have negative effects on mental health and general well -being, especially in young people. This behavior can be related to depression, anxiety, sleep disorders, low self -esteem and social isolation.  Effects of excessive use of social networks: Mental health: the excessive use of social networks has been related to an increase in the appearance of mental health problems such as depression, anxiety, sleep disorders and self -esteem problems, especially in young people.  Academic performance: Social networks addiction can interfere with academic study and performance, causing lack of attention and concentration problems.  Social relations: excessive use of social networks can lead to the negligence of social relations in real life and the difficulty in connecting with other people.  Physical health: Sedentary lifestyle associated with prolonged use of social networks can contribute to physical health problems, according to mind.  Sleep problems: the use of electronic devices before sleeping, such as phones and tablets, can disturb sleep and contribute to sleep problems.  Body image and self -esteem: Social networks can encourage constant comparison with others and create unrealistic expectations about body and life, which can damage self -esteem and body image, reports the Child Mind Institute.  Social isolation: excessive use of social networks can lead to social isolation, since people can spend more time online than interacting with others in person.  Cybercase and risks: the use of social networks can expose people to risks such as cyberbullying, exploitation and online scam.  Tips for reducing the excessive use of social networks: Establishing time limits: Mark time limits for the use of social networks and adhere to them can help avoid excessive use.  Disable notifications: Disable notifications of social networks can help reducing the temptation to constantly verify updates.  Prioritize out -line activities: getting hooked on off -line activities, such as sports, hobbies or hobbies, can help reduce the time spent on social networks.  Promoting face -to -face communication: looking for opportunities to interact with others in person can help balance the use of social networks with social relations in real life.  Finding professional help: if the use of social networks becomes compulsive or significantly affects well -being, it may be useful to seek professional help from a psychologist or psychiatrist. The case of Josef Fritzl, known as the "Amstetten Monster", is one of the most shocking and disturbing crimes in Austria's history. For 24 years, Fritzl kept his own daughter, Elisabeth Fritzl, captive in a secret basement under her home, subjecting her to terrible abuse.

In 1984, when Elisabeth was 18 years old, Josef Fritzl cheated her to go down to her home in Amstetten, where she locked her in a hidden room. He told his wife and the authorities that Elisabeth had escaped and joined a sect, while, in reality, she remained prisoner underground. During the next 24 years, Fritzl submitted Elisabeth to an inhuman treatment, which resulted in the birth of seven children. Three of these children were raised in captivity with Elisabeth, while another three were "adopted" by Fritzl and his wife, with the excuse that Elisabeth had left them abandoned at the door of the house.

The situation began to crumble in 2008, when one of the daughters born in captivity, Kerstin, seriously ill. Fritzl allowed Kerstin to be taken to the hospital, which caused an investigation that finally revealed the horrible secret that had been hidden for more than two decades. The authorities discovered Elisabeth and her children in the basement, where they had lived in deplorable conditions and without contact with the outside world.

In 2009, Josef Fritzl was taken to trial, where he confessed all his crimes. He was convicted of multiple serious crimes, including kidnapping, negligence that led to the death of one of the babies, and slavery. Fritzl was sentenced to life imprisonment in a high security prison.

The case of Josef Fritzl shocked not only Austria, but the entire world, not only for the cruelty of the crime, but for the duration of the same and the fact that it was committed in the apparent normality of a residential neighborhood. The story of Elisabeth Fritzl and her children symbolizes the incredible human capacity to survive before extreme conditions and also highlights the failures in social systems that did not detect this horror for so long.

Bridge addiction ⬇️ Social networks were not designed to inform you or entertain you. They were designed to capture your attention for as long as possible. Sea Parker said it, former Facebook president: "We create Facebook to generate addicts." And it works. Because?   Because every notification, like or scroll generates a microchispazo of dopamine, the pleasure hormone. That activates the same reward circuit that is seen in addictions such as game, drugs or pornography. The result?  A cycle that hooks, exhausts and disconnects us from the present. According to the psychiatrist @marianrojasstape_oficial: ➡️ This constant stimulation affects key brain areas such as prefrontal cortex, related to self -control and attention. ➡️ Anxiety increases, reduce concentration and make it more difficult to control impulses. ➡️ And the most worrying: excessive use is normalized from an early age ... by adults themselves. It is not about eliminating technology. It's about understanding how it works, to use it with conscience. #Digitaldetox #Modopresentient #lesspantallasvida #hanadigitaldetox #doomscrolling #saludmento #addiction adispositives #marianrojas stapé #Equilibriodigital #ReDeDeDESOCIALS #ANXIUSGENERATION #AADICCIONES

Dysmorphia is basically when the brain does not process how you look, as if it were always using a distorted filter. Studies show that some connections in the brain may be overactive, especially those that control how we perceive our image. Something that can help is to train the mind with techniques such as gradual exposure and change certain automatic thoughts. This teaches the brain to interpret things more realistically over time. Child sexual abuse is an extremely serious and worrying issue that can have devastating consequences in the lives of children who suffer from it. It is crucial to address this issue with sensitivity and awareness, providing support for victims and working to prevent future cases. Speaking to children by their names to the body parts, instead of using vague terms or euphemisms, is an important way to empower them and educate them about their own body. This helps them to understand their anatomy precisely and to communicate clearly if any situation makes them feel uncomfortable or insecure. By using the correct names of the body parts, trust is encouraged, open communication is promoted and shame around issues related to sexuality and intimacy is reduced. It is also essential to teach children about personal limits and mutual respect, which can contribute to preventing situations of sexual abuse. It is important to remember that the prevention of child sexual abuse implies education, awareness and the creation of safe environments where children feel protected and heard. If you suspect that a child is being a victim of sexual abuse, it is essential to act immediately and seek professional help. (woman), stepfather and mother of the victim, for the crimes of violation and family violence, committed to the grievance of a woman since she was four years old, events that occurred in the region of the Papaloapan basin. The criminal complaint made by the victim, details that, since he was four years old (today adult), he was assaulted in different ways by his stepfather, who threatened her to remain silent, despite that, he told her mother who did not believe her. As a consequence of these abuses, the victim was pregnant and gave birth, the newborn was registered as daughter of her stepfather and her mother, who stripped her of the baby, made in the region of the Papaloapan basin. Finally, the victim denounced in May 2025, so the Oaxaca Prosecutor's Office initiated investigations with a gender perspective, through the Regional ViceFiscalía of the Basin.  As a result of the ministerial works, the arrest warrants were obtained by which, elements of the State Investigation Agency (AEI), in collaboration with the National Defense Secretariat (Defense), set up an operation thanks to which they arrested A.G.R. (man) and J.R.A. (woman), who were available to the corresponding authority to define their legal status. The Attorney General of the State of Oaxaca has among its priorities to guarantee a life free of violence for women, and adolescents, through the justice procurement mechanisms that are in charge of specialized areas.

Verbal bullying involves the use of words, language, or verbal aggression to demean, insult, intimidate, or humiliate another person. It can include name-calling, teasing, mocking, spreading rumors, making derogatory comments, or using offensive language. Verbal bullying can be both direct, happening face-to-face, or indirect, such as through gossip or spreading hurtful messages.
It's important to note that bullying can manifest in other forms as well, including physical bullying (such as hitting, pushing, or physical intimidation), relational or social bullying (such as excluding, spreading rumors, or manipulating social relationships), and cyberbullying (using electronic devices or online platforms to harass, threaten, or humiliate others).
Bullying behavior is harmful and can have severe consequences for the individuals targeted, including emotional distress, decreased self-esteem, anxiety, depression, and even physical injuries. It's crucial to address and prevent bullying by promoting empathy, respect, inclusion, and creating safe environments where individuals feel supported and protected. #Textpledge #Riseup #NoBullying #EndBullying

You’re not just “on your phone too much.” You’re probably dopamine-drunk. Here’s the harsh truth: social media is the new drug and many of us are addicted without even realizing it. Every scroll, every swipe, every flashy video floods your brain with dopamine which is your brain’s “feel good” chemical. But just like with drugs, when the high wears off, you crash. You feel restless. You lose motivation. You can’t focus. You chase another hit… and another… and another. It’s not you lacking discipline. It’s your brain being hijacked. And it’s not just “harmless entertainment.” This overstimulation can rewire your brain’s reward system. That’s why reading a book suddenly feels boring. That’s why silence feels uncomfortable. That’s why focus feels like punishment. You’re not weak. You’re overstimulated. If you're tired of feeling mentally exhausted and emotionally fried then put the phone down. Get quiet. Reclaim your attention. Your mind is not a playground for algorithms. Your peace is the real flex. #dopaminedetox  #mentalhealthawareness

Telephone addiction, also known as nomophobia or addiction to mobile devices, can have various negative consequences both physically and emotional and socially. Some of the possible consequences of the phone addiction are the following:

Social isolation: people addicted to the phone may experience difficulties in interacting and interacting with other people in the real world. Spending too much time on the phone can lead to social isolation, affecting family, friendship and labor relations.

Deterioration of interpersonal relationships: phone addiction can interfere with personal relationships, since addicted people can neglect their loved ones, ignore conversations or show lack of interest in shared activities.

Low academic or work performance: spending too much time on the phone can affect work performance or studies. Constant distraction and difficulty concentrating can reduce productivity and achievement of goals.

Sleep problems: excessive use of the phone before sleeping can interfere with sleep. The blue light emitted by mobile devices can alter circadian rhythms and hinder the start and quality of sleep.

Physical health problems: passing long periods of time using the phone can cause physical problems such as headaches, eye fatigue, neck pain and back due to bad posture, and carpal tunnel syndrome in your hands.

Anxiety and stress: Telephone addiction can generate anxiety and stress due to the constant need to be connected, review notifications or keep up with social networks. The telephone dependence can generate fear of missing something important (Fomo) and generate a feeling of always being "connected."

I’ve been struggling with social media addiction recently. If you have too, you are not alone.  

#socialmediaaddiction #socialmedia #mentalhealth #fypシ

social media feels like one big competition 

who can start the most hobbies, who can stay awake for the longest, who can be the most productive, who can travel the most 

and i absolutely LOVE that it is pushing people to be the best version of themselves and inspiring people to enjoy their lives for the fullest, i really do 

but it can make the rest of us just feel ‘boring’. I’ve been stuck in a limbo of feeling undeserving of a platform, like there’s so much pressure to do things ‘worthy’ of posting. like my day to day life isn’t good enough to share. because all I’m exposed to is beautiful holiday pictures and incredible outfits.

this even sounds silly now I’m typing it out, because I know deep down that I have this platform to share normal life. I want to be a space where you feel comforted, where you don’t feel pressure and don’t feel the need to compare. where you can just be, and be ‘normal’ and be okay with that 

I just constantly feel boring. I wake up, I work, I eat, I go to sleep. I don’t travel, I occasionally go for a coffee, I barely get dressed. it’s 2pm as I’m typing this and I haven’t brushed my teeth lmao. but that’s just real, and social media has fed us SO much information that real life is now boring. 

 so I’m here to show you that it’s not <3 and even if it is, there’s nothing wrong with it, and you are good enough, and you are allowed to just be. comparison is the thief of joy ⭐️

The benefits ⬇️ How many times, looking in the mirror, did you start listing your shortcomings? "Big belly", "fat hips", "wrinkles", "cellulite" ... is familiar?  The time has come to stop this war and begin to see beauty and value in your body. Why are we so often criticized by ourselves? • Social pressure: unrealistic standards of beauty from advertising, magazines and social networks are constantly hit by us. We begin to compare ourselves with "ideal" pictures and feel inferior. • Negative beliefs: in childhood, we could tell us that we are “fat”, “ugly” or “awkward”. These words are imprinted in our memory and affect our self -perception. • Perfectionism: we strive for perfection in everything, including in our appearance. Any deviation from the "ideal" causes us disappointment and self -criticism. Dietary culture: everyone monitors themselves and therefore try various power systems in order to reduce weight, which again forces to hide on numbers on scales and appearance. How to stop criticizing yourself and love your body? • Be realized your thoughts: notice the moments when you begin to criticize yourself. Stop and ask yourself: "Is it true? Is it really so important?" • Focus on your merits: make a list of your virtues - not only external, but also internal. Remember what you love in yourself, which makes you unique. • Thank your body: every day thank your body for what it does for you. For the fact that it allows you to move, see, hear, feel. Cellular addiction in children? Let's take action! Hello everyone! Have you noticed how children spend more time glued to the cell phone? Technology is an incredible tool, but we must take into account the impact it can have on our little ones. Today I want to talk to you about cell phone addiction in children, their origins, consequences and how we can help prevent this problem. First, how does cell phone addiction originate in children? The answer is simple: the easy access and use of mobile devices. Children are increasingly experts in the use of technology and most of them have their own cell phone. However, the problem is that many parents do not establish limits of use or supervision, which can lead to excessive and unhealthy use. The consequences of cell phone addiction in children can be serious. They can develop attention problems, social isolation, sleep problems and a decrease in learning quality. In addition, children can be vulnerable to inappropriate content online and cyber harassment. To help with this problem, it is important to establish clear and firm limits in the use of cell phone. Some recommendations include establishing specific schedules for the use of cell phone, establishing areas free of technology at home and talking with children about the responsible use of technology. It is also important to supervise the content to which children have access and have open and honest conversations about online risks. In summary, cell phone addiction in children is a real problem, but there are measures that we can take to help prevent it. Establishing clear limits and supervising the use of technology can help our children develop a healthy and responsible use of the cell phone. Let's take care of our little ones and encourage a positive use of technology! What do you think should be done in these cases? #Children #celular #Adiccion #Venezuela #vzla #Adccioncion

Fatal familial insomnia is a very rare and invariably fatal autosomal dominant neurodegenerative prion disease caused by a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Hallmarks of the disease include aggressively progressive insomnia, subsequent autonomic disturbances, including tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, and hypertension, cognitive disturbances including deficits in short-term memory and attention, balance problems, and endocrine dysfunction. 

The disease is currently incurable and has an average duration of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. This activity describes the pathophysiology, presentation, and management of fatal familial insomnia and highlights the role of the interprofessional team in the care of affected patients and families.

Fatal familial insomnia (FFI) is a remarkably rare and invariably fatal inherited neurodegenerative prion disease. The mode of inheritance of this disease is autosomal dominant and involves a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Aggressively progressive insomnia, with subsequent autonomic (tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, hypertension), cognitive (short-term memory and attentional deficits), motor system (balance problems), and endocrine dysfunction are a hallmark of the disease. The disease is currently incurable and has a mean course of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. 

The earliest description of the disease dates back to 1765 with a report of an Italian man with symptoms suggestive of FFI. The disease was formally identified and clinically described in 1986 by Lugaresi E. et al., followed by subsequent studies, further describing its pathophysiology, etiology, and clinical course. 

Genetic prion diseases are very rare. Annually, there are 1 to 1.5 new cases of genetic and non-genetic prion diseases per one million people. Genetic forms of prion disease constitute approximately 10% of the total cases of prion diseases. FFI is exceptionally rare with the disease-causing mutation found in around 50 families worldwide. 

Patients with fatal familial insomnia (FFI) most commonly present between the ages of 20 and 61 years with a mean of 50 years and it affects males and females equally.

Body Dysmorphia explained  Also known as BDD (body dysmorphic disorder) is a mental health condition where you become fixated with how your appearance You may have body dysmorphic disorder if you worry a lot about how a specific part of your body looks and it affects your daily life It can often look like nothing to most people but to you will seem massive. You can become fixated on what you perceive as imperfection and flaws and worry about how you can change them. This can bring around anxiety and lead to other mental health disorders. The exact cause of body dysmorphic disorder is unclear. It’s been linked to genes, chemical changes in the brain and traumatic past experiences Also, as females, the way society has such intense pressures on us to look a certain way - and this changes all the time to whatever is the latest beauty trend - but our bodies are NOT trends This is something I work with a lot of women on in order to reframe their mindset to feel their best - as I always say, your mental health is just as important as your physical - and my coaching goes way beyond just a workout plans and some calories  Please know you’re not alone in feeling this way and you can reach out for help, even talking about it can feel like a load lifted - a problem shared is a problem halved  #bodydysmorphia #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealthmatters #keepingitreal #gymgirl #realness #mindsetcoach #bodydysmorphiawareness #mentalhealth

Body dysmorphia is a mental disorder where the body's self -perception is altered and the aspects that we do not like in an exaggerated way are seen. Those who develop this disorder feel the need to modify the appearance of their body radically or see it as the only solution to feel good, so in many cases they try all means to achieve that desired physical change. . In very extreme cases, the hypothetical defect to correct does not even exist under objective criteria and in the other cases, those features that move away from the standards of social beauty or those of the person in particular, are perceived in a very exaggerated way. In very often nutritional sessions we can identify risk behaviors in relation to this problem, so it is important Perfectionism, discrimination) • The importance of food as a basic need more than a tool for physical objective • Avoid body checking or hyper control of the body • Include your body in pleasure activities (learn something new, pleasant without use of physical objectives, moments of calm) • Alternative therapy: Tapping, breathing technique, relaxation, mindfulness, statements, meditation. After 3 years on social media, I’ve made the incredibly difficult decision to step away. This isn’t a goodbye filled with drama — it’s a quiet exit to protect my peace.

Over time, the negativity and bullying became too much. I tried to push through, to stay strong, to not let it get to me… but the truth is, words hurt. And no matter how many amazing, supportive people were here (and I’ll never forget you), the constant hate started to drown out the joy I once felt creating and sharing my life with you.

I’m proud of what I built, the connections I made, and the growth I’ve seen in myself along the way. But now, I choose healing. I choose to step away from a space that no longer feels safe for me.

Please be kind to people online. You never know what someone is carrying.

To those who showed me love, encouragement, and genuine support — thank you. You helped me more than you’ll ever know. I’m not sure if or when I’ll return, but for now, I’m focusing on me.

Fatal familial insomnia is a very rare and invariably fatal autosomal dominant neurodegenerative prion disease caused by a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Hallmarks of the disease include aggressively progressive insomnia, subsequent autonomic disturbances, including tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, and hypertension, cognitive disturbances including deficits in short-term memory and attention, balance problems, and endocrine dysfunction. 

The disease is currently incurable and has an average duration of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. This activity describes the pathophysiology, presentation, and management of fatal familial insomnia and highlights the role of the interprofessional team in the care of affected patients and families.

Fatal familial insomnia (FFI) is a remarkably rare and invariably fatal inherited neurodegenerative prion disease. The mode of inheritance of this disease is autosomal dominant and involves a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Aggressively progressive insomnia, with subsequent autonomic (tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, hypertension), cognitive (short-term memory and attentional deficits), motor system (balance problems), and endocrine dysfunction are a hallmark of the disease. The disease is currently incurable and has a mean course of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. 

The earliest description of the disease dates back to 1765 with a report of an Italian man with symptoms suggestive of FFI. The disease was formally identified and clinically described in 1986 by Lugaresi E. et al., followed by subsequent studies, further describing its pathophysiology, etiology, and clinical course. 

Genetic prion diseases are very rare. Annually, there are 1 to 1.5 new cases of genetic and non-genetic prion diseases per one million people. Genetic forms of prion disease constitute approximately 10% of the total cases of prion diseases. FFI is exceptionally rare with the disease-causing mutation found in around 50 families worldwide. 

Patients with fatal familial insomnia (FFI) most commonly present between the ages of 20 and 61 years with a mean of 50 years and it affects males and females equally.

TW: Body dysmorphia
Body dysmorphia, i.e. a bodily dysmorphic disorder, which is characterized by constant fears of unsightly appearance or body structure. Other symptoms are: frequent viewing in mirrors, focusing only on defects, a sense of being assessed by the defect, obsessive attempts to hide the defect, social withdrawal, low self -esteem, lack of willingness to work. 

This disorder or its symptoms affect more and more people nowadays due to the increasingly developing artificial intelligence that "produces" the unattainable canon of appearance. In social media, people show their best shots. This leads to unreal standards that we set for ourselves to achieve. 

Unlike universal opinion, people who go to the gym often struggle with this disorder. Even a person who has a figure of dreams in the eyes of others may suffer internally about dysmorphic disorder and see himself and his completely different body - as in a distorting mirror. As in the above video, perception of your own body can change over the days or even hours, but it has nothing to do with reality. 

Remember that you are not alone in it. If you suffer from body dysmorphie and it significantly affects your mental state, well -being and functioning - consult your fears with a psychologist.

Cars today account for about 8 million tonnes of carbon emissions in Sweden. Should everyone ride a bus, this would be drastically reduced, explanation: According to Swedish public transport (industry organization for Sweden's county traffic), 95% of buses in Sweden is run on fossil -free fuels and 8% is powered by electricity (about 1100 buses). With that assumption, 87% are biofuels (biogas, RME, HVO, etc), 8% electric drive and remaining (5%) fossil fuels. Emissions for one electric bus per kilometer is 10g, for biofuels about 5-15g depending on the choice of fuel (but we say 10g here too) and for fossil fuels about 30g. About 5 million in Sweden owns a car. An annual mileage for a passenger car is 13,000 km which means we can get total PKM if we do (13,000 km x 5 million) which gives us 65 billion PKM. The state emissions per PKM is 11G if we use the values ​​for fossil -free (electricity and biofuels) and fossil buses that we previously calculated. This means that if we also use it with the total PKM value we calculated, this means that the total emissions for buses would be around 715,000 tonnes (65 billion x 11g) per year if all who own a car switched to bus. If emissions with passenger cars are 8 million tonnes, we can calculate the difference between emissions from cars by buses by multiplying 8 million by 0.715, which would give us about 7.3 million tonnes per year. It is thus the reduction of carbon dioxide emissions if everyone were to ride a bus instead of a car. #Croller Transport #lookal Traffic #buses #tiktoksverige #svenskatok #sverige #pre -digit

Reactive Abuse Reactive abuse is a term used to describe a situation where a victim of abuse reacts to the abuser’s behavior—often in a heightened emotional or even aggressive way—and then the abuser uses that reaction to portray the victim as the actual abuser. Here’s how it usually plays out: 	1.	The abuser provokes the victim through manipulation, gaslighting, verbal, emotional, or even physical abuse. 	2.	The victim, after prolonged exposure or being pushed too far, lashes out—they might yell, cry, throw something, or try to defend themselves. 	3.	The abuser then points to that reaction as proof that the victim is “crazy,” “toxic,” or the one who is abusive. This tactic can be especially damaging because: 	•	It makes the victim question their own behavior. 	•	It gives the abuser a way to justify their actions. 	•	Outsiders may only see the victim’s explosive reaction, not the long-term abuse that led up to it. It’s important to recognize reactive abuse not as a justification for harmful behavior, but as a trauma response—and it shouldn’t be confused with mutual abuse, which involves consistent abuse from both parties. Fatal familial insomnia is a very rare and invariably fatal autosomal dominant neurodegenerative prion disease caused by a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Hallmarks of the disease include aggressively progressive insomnia, subsequent autonomic disturbances, including tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, and hypertension, cognitive disturbances including deficits in short-term memory and attention, balance problems, and endocrine dysfunction. 

The disease is currently incurable and has an average duration of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. This activity describes the pathophysiology, presentation, and management of fatal familial insomnia and highlights the role of the interprofessional team in the care of affected patients and families.

Fatal familial insomnia (FFI) is a remarkably rare and invariably fatal inherited neurodegenerative prion disease. The mode of inheritance of this disease is autosomal dominant and involves a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Aggressively progressive insomnia, with subsequent autonomic (tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, hypertension), cognitive (short-term memory and attentional deficits), motor system (balance problems), and endocrine dysfunction are a hallmark of the disease. The disease is currently incurable and has a mean course of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. 

The earliest description of the disease dates back to 1765 with a report of an Italian man with symptoms suggestive of FFI. The disease was formally identified and clinically described in 1986 by Lugaresi E. et al., followed by subsequent studies, further describing its pathophysiology, etiology, and clinical course. 

Genetic prion diseases are very rare. Annually, there are 1 to 1.5 new cases of genetic and non-genetic prion diseases per one million people. Genetic forms of prion disease constitute approximately 10% of the total cases of prion diseases. FFI is exceptionally rare with the disease-causing mutation found in around 50 families worldwide. 

Patients with fatal familial insomnia (FFI) most commonly present between the ages of 20 and 61 years with a mean of 50 years and it affects males and females equally.

The Social Dilemma (2020) is a documentary that shows us how social networks mold our habits, decisions and even our perception of reality. With testimonies of former Google, Facebook and Twitter workers, it exposes how algorithms are designed to capture our attention at any cost, generating addiction, polarization and disinformation. More than a technological criticism, it is an urgent call to reflect on the use we make of the platforms and how they silently influence everyday life.

The cell phone, in itself, is not a destructive tool. Like many technologies, its impact depends on ** use that we give **. However, the ** excessive and uncontrolled use ** of the cell phone can become a ** addiction ** that, unfortunately, can seriously damage the lives of Christians in several crucial aspects:

When the cell phone becomes the center of our attention and time, we can be, without realizing it, raising it to a place that only corresponds to God. We spend more time sliding our finger on the screen than ** in prayer, reading the Bible, or meditating ** in your word. This priority detour can lead to:

*** Loss of intimacy with God: ** The relationship with God requires time, stillness and focus. The constant notification bombardment and the temptation to review the phone interrupt these sacred moments, causing the voice of God to drown in digital noise.
*** Spiritual superficiality: ** If our spiritual "food" is based on rapid fragments of social networks or short videos, we lose the depth of meditation in the Scriptures and the systematic study that nourishes a robust faith.

The cell phone can create a ** false connection sensation ** while isolates real and significant relationships.

*** Family distancing: ** Instead of talking or sharing with the family, each member can be absorbed on their own device. This mine communication, empathy and construction of strong ties that are fundamental to a Christian home. The physical presence does not guarantee the emotional connection.
*** Affectation of communion in the Church: ** During services, meetings or biblical studies, the temptation to review the cell phone can steal attention, active participation and genuine connection with other believers. The distraction prevents us from edifying each other as the body of Christ.

The misuse of the cell phone generates a series of behaviors that are contrary to growth in faith:

*** Attention and concentration deficit: ** The constant exposure to fragmented information and instant gratification trains our mind for distraction. This hinders the prolonged reading of the Bible, deep prayer and attentive listening to preaching, activities that demand concentration.
*** Comparison and envy: ** Social networks often show idealized versions of the lives of others, which can lead to comparison, envy, dissatisfaction and low self -esteem, feelings that undermine gratitude and contenture that promotes faith.
*** harmful content and temptations: ** The ease of access to immoral, violent or inappropriate content can expose the believer to temptations and pollute his mind and spirit, moving it away from the purity and holiness to which we are called.
*** Loss of valuable time: ** The hours dedicated to an irreflexive consumption of content or endless "scrolling are hours that could devote themselves to serve God, help others, study or rest properly.

The problem is not the cell phone itself, but our ** inability to exercise self -control ** on its use (2 Timothy 1: 7). Christians are called to live with ** wisdom and discernment ** (Ephesians 5: 15-16), taking advantage of time and putting God in the first place of our lives.

If we allow the cell phone to occupy the place of God, the family, the church and its word, then, yes, the cell phone becomes a tool that, unintentionally, ** destroys the foundations of the Christian life. ** #prayer

How much privacy do you really have on social networks?

We live in a hyperconnected world, where it is common to see publications of every everyday moment: what we eat, where we are, what we do. But have you stopped to think about the impact of this? The constant exposure on social networks can not only lead us to an empty life of meaning, but it feeds a global system where our human essence is diluted.

 Privacy is your best shield on the Internet. Each photo, each publication is a fragment of you that delivers an environment where the data is gold. Do not fall into the game of a constant exhibition that consumes your essence. Take care what you share and remember that privacy gives you power and protects you in an increasingly guarded world.

✋ Reflect and set limits: preserve your privacy and discover a more genuine connection with yourself and with the world around you.

Adrian Jones was a 7-year-old boy from Kansas City, Kansas, whose case is one of the most horrifying examples of long-term child abuse in U.S. history. 

From 2013 to 2015, Adrian lived with his biological father, Michael Jones, and his stepmother, Heather Jones. Instead of being cared for, Adrian was held captive, starved, beaten, restrained, and subjected to extreme neglect and mental torment — often in ways that were captured on the couple’s own surveillance system inside the home.

Photos later recovered showed Adrian emaciated, locked inside a shower stall, and forced to stand for hours without food or water. He was so thin, his bones were clearly visible. Despite clear warning signs and past reports to child protective services, Adrian remained in that home — unseen and unheard — until it was too late.

In November 2015, police were called to the family’s home for a domestic incident, but what they found was worse than anyone imagined. Adrian had been deceased for weeks. His remains were discovered inside a livestock pen on the property — because after everything they did to him, they fed his body to pigs.

Michael and Heather Jones were both sentenced to life in prison. But many still ask how so many adults and agencies failed a child who was literally begging for help in documented video footage. Adrian’s story is a tragic reminder of what can happen when no one listens.

TW: Body dysmorphia
Body dysmorphia, i.e. a bodily dysmorphic disorder, which is characterized by constant fears of unsightly appearance or body structure. Other symptoms are: frequent viewing in mirrors, focusing only on defects, a sense of being assessed by the defect, obsessive attempts to hide the defect, social withdrawal, low self -esteem, lack of willingness to work. 

This disorder or its symptoms affect more and more people nowadays due to the increasingly developing artificial intelligence that "produces" the unattainable canon of appearance. In social media, people show their best shots. This leads to unreal standards that we set for ourselves to achieve. 

Unlike universal opinion, people who go to the gym often struggle with this disorder. Even a person who has a figure of dreams in the eyes of others may suffer internally about dysmorphic disorder and see himself and his completely different body - as in a distorting mirror. As in the above video, perception of your own body can change over the days or even hours, but it has nothing to do with reality. 

Remember that you are not alone in it. If you suffer from body dysmorphie and it significantly affects your mental state, well -being and functioning - consult your fears with a psychologist.

Fatal familial insomnia is a very rare and invariably fatal autosomal dominant neurodegenerative prion disease caused by a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Hallmarks of the disease include aggressively progressive insomnia, subsequent autonomic disturbances, including tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, and hypertension, cognitive disturbances including deficits in short-term memory and attention, balance problems, and endocrine dysfunction. 

The disease is currently incurable and has an average duration of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. This activity describes the pathophysiology, presentation, and management of fatal familial insomnia and highlights the role of the interprofessional team in the care of affected patients and families.

Fatal familial insomnia (FFI) is a remarkably rare and invariably fatal inherited neurodegenerative prion disease. The mode of inheritance of this disease is autosomal dominant and involves a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Aggressively progressive insomnia, with subsequent autonomic (tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, hypertension), cognitive (short-term memory and attentional deficits), motor system (balance problems), and endocrine dysfunction are a hallmark of the disease. The disease is currently incurable and has a mean course of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. 

The earliest description of the disease dates back to 1765 with a report of an Italian man with symptoms suggestive of FFI. The disease was formally identified and clinically described in 1986 by Lugaresi E. et al., followed by subsequent studies, further describing its pathophysiology, etiology, and clinical course. 

Genetic prion diseases are very rare. Annually, there are 1 to 1.5 new cases of genetic and non-genetic prion diseases per one million people. Genetic forms of prion disease constitute approximately 10% of the total cases of prion diseases. FFI is exceptionally rare with the disease-causing mutation found in around 50 families worldwide. 

Patients with fatal familial insomnia (FFI) most commonly present between the ages of 20 and 61 years with a mean of 50 years and it affects males and females equally.

We were not in the streets until they forced us there with their horses. That’s when they closed in on us from all corners. My camera captured several angles showing cops and sheriffs blocking us in. Stop telling us we could’ve left No we couldn’t.  “Just say you did nothing wrong.” We said that.  We communicated we were just trying to go home. Most of us had ID’s on us We were told to cooperate and informed we were all under arrest for Penal Code 409. We were not given any dispersal announcement. We were held in that blockade for an hour and arrested at 8 PM conveniently the DTLA curfew for certain areas. We were detained, bussed to south LA and held until they processed our information and issued us citations. I appreciate everyone checking in. This was small compared to what migrant families are going through. I hope you all continue to show up  Side note  Stop telling people what they should have done when you weren’t there and have not found yourself in a situation like it.  No one went anticipating to be arrested especially before the curfew and especially when there was NO violence. I’m open to hearing from those who have been in this situation, and to learning your best practices.

Social media is designed to be as addicting as possible (cuz we gotta get those ad dollars baby!) and without a strategy to counter it, it’s almost impossible to avoid getting swept in. 

Developing a strategy to counter the addiction that companies place within us is imperative to creating meaningful sustained action in the real world.

Why after a break someone who never climbed anything into networks, suddenly becomes more active than an influencer?

From psychology, this can have several explanations:

 Search for external validation: When breaking a link, some people try to fill the emotional vacuum receiving attention or compliments by networks.

 Defense mechanism: publishing constantly can be a way of denying pain, projecting happiness or "overcoming" when internally they are still processing loss.

 Indirect message: Sometimes, it becomes a way of saying "Look at me, I'm better without you", even if you don't say with words.

 Reconnection with identity: During a relationship many people go out, they lose or adapt so much that they forget who they were. Network exposure can be a way to return to themselves ... or at least try.

 Not everything you see in networks is happiness, sometimes it is just a way to survive duel.

Fatal familial insomnia is a very rare and invariably fatal autosomal dominant neurodegenerative prion disease caused by a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene.  Hallmarks of the disease include aggressively progressive insomnia, subsequent autonomic disturbances, including tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, and hypertension, cognitive disturbances including deficits in short-term memory and attention, balance problems, and endocrine dysfunction.  The disease is currently incurable and has an average duration of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. This activity describes the pathophysiology, presentation, and management of fatal familial insomnia and highlights the role of the interprofessional team in the care of affected patients and families. Fatal familial insomnia (FFI) is a remarkably rare and invariably fatal inherited neurodegenerative prion disease. The mode of inheritance of this disease is autosomal dominant and involves a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene.  Aggressively progressive insomnia, with subsequent autonomic (tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, hypertension), cognitive (short-term memory and attentional deficits), motor system (balance problems), and endocrine dysfunction are a hallmark of the disease. The disease is currently incurable and has a mean course of 18 months, ultimately leading to death.  The earliest description of the disease dates back to 1765 with a report of an Italian man with symptoms suggestive of FFI. The disease was formally identified and clinically described in 1986 by Lugaresi E. et al., followed by subsequent studies, further describing its pathophysiology, etiology, and clinical course.  Genetic prion diseases are very rare. Annually, there are 1 to 1.5 new cases of genetic and non-genetic prion diseases per one million people. Genetic forms of prion disease constitute approximately 10% of the total cases of prion diseases. FFI is exceptionally rare with the disease-causing mutation found in around 50 families worldwide.  Patients with fatal familial insomnia (FFI) most commonly present between the ages of 20 and 61 years with a mean of 50 years and it affects males and females equally.  #fyp #fypシ #FFI #fatalfamilialinsomnia #insomnia #disturbing #1990s #horror #scary #camcorder

Fatal familial insomnia is a very rare and invariably fatal autosomal dominant neurodegenerative prion disease caused by a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Hallmarks of the disease include aggressively progressive insomnia, subsequent autonomic disturbances, including tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, and hypertension, cognitive disturbances including deficits in short-term memory and attention, balance problems, and endocrine dysfunction. 

The disease is currently incurable and has an average duration of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. This activity describes the pathophysiology, presentation, and management of fatal familial insomnia and highlights the role of the interprofessional team in the care of affected patients and families.

Fatal familial insomnia (FFI) is a remarkably rare and invariably fatal inherited neurodegenerative prion disease. The mode of inheritance of this disease is autosomal dominant and involves a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Aggressively progressive insomnia, with subsequent autonomic (tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, hypertension), cognitive (short-term memory and attentional deficits), motor system (balance problems), and endocrine dysfunction are a hallmark of the disease. The disease is currently incurable and has a mean course of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. 

The earliest description of the disease dates back to 1765 with a report of an Italian man with symptoms suggestive of FFI. The disease was formally identified and clinically described in 1986 by Lugaresi E. et al., followed by subsequent studies, further describing its pathophysiology, etiology, and clinical course. 

Genetic prion diseases are very rare. Annually, there are 1 to 1.5 new cases of genetic and non-genetic prion diseases per one million people. Genetic forms of prion disease constitute approximately 10% of the total cases of prion diseases. FFI is exceptionally rare with the disease-causing mutation found in around 50 families worldwide. 

Patients with fatal familial insomnia (FFI) most commonly present between the ages of 20 and 61 years with a mean of 50 years and it affects males and females equally.

You train, you eat well, you take care of yourself ... and you still don't like what you see in the mirror

That is called body dysmorphia, and more common than you think.

Feeling "small", "fat" or "insufficient" even if you are better than ever ... it is part of something deeper that is not resolved with another series.

Not everything is fixed with muscle. Sometimes, you also have to work your head.

Your progress is worth. Your body deserves respect, even when it is not "perfect."

And you deserve to look with the same eyes with which you admire others.

Actually the reasons for this behavior can be multiple, here I put them

However, experiential avoidance 
It could be one of the possible causes:
 ✨ Experiential avoidance is when a person does everything possible for not feeling or facing unpleasant emotions or memories. 
✅In time of accepting what you are feeling, try to suppress it, distract or escape in some way. 

Eliminate social networks could be a way to avoid contacting pain or related emotions 
 
However, this is not the only one and we are all different so we face different ways 
Other associated causes: 

✨✅ Mental Health: Networks can cause anxiety, stress or depression, especially when you compare yourself with others, you feel exposed or simply overwhelms you so much information.
	✅ Time dummy: Many people feel that they spend too much time in networks without realizing it, and eliminating apps is a way to recover that time for other more significant things.
	✅ Need for disconnection: Sometimes, only one respite is needed. Being available or connected can become exhausting, and disconnecting is a way of reconnecting with oneself.
	✅ Privacy: The fear that their personal data is being used or shared without control also leads many people to close their accounts.
	✅ Social or image: in networks we feel the need to show a "perfect life." Some get tired of maintaining that facade or feel they lose authenticity.
	✅ Stage changes: Some people eliminate their networks when closing cycles, such as after a break, at the beginning of a new project, or simply to start from scratch.
	✅ Digital addiction: when they realize that they cannot stop reviewing the cell phone, although there is nothing new, and that affects their concentration or personal relationships.

Insomnia is like your body wanting sleep but your brain deciding it’s time to solve all of life’s problems instead. You can be lying in bed, lights off, blanket pulled up, doing everything right—but your brain goes, “Hey, remember that one embarrassing thing you said in 6th grade?” or “Let’s plan out your whole life right now.” And suddenly, you’re just… awake.

Sometimes insomnia feels like you’re stuck in a tug-of-war with your own mind. You want rest. Your eyes feel heavy. But the moment you close them, a random song plays on repeat in your head, or your thoughts start running a mental marathon. You try breathing exercises, you flip the pillow to the cool side, you try counting sheep—but even the sheep are like, “Dude, we’re tired too.”

And the next day hits different. You’re not even tired in a sleepy way—you’re tired in a slow Wi-Fi kind of way. Everything takes longer to load: your focus, your patience, your ability to remember why you walked into a room.

Insomnia isn’t just missing sleep—it’s battling your brain at 2 a.m. and losing the argument every time.

Do you have a phone addiction? ✨ Summary 1️⃣ Stop having your mobile always by hand. Move it physically helps you break the automatic habit of looking at it without thinking. 2️⃣ Remember that the impulse does not only come from your mind, but of your body. Your cells look for dopamine and push that behavior. 3️⃣⏸️ Decide when you are going to use the mobile and when not. Putting clear limits reinforces your self -control and improves your well -being. 4️⃣ Avoid constant dopamine peaks. The more artificial dopamine generes, the less space you leave for real happiness. 5️⃣ Do not fall into the self -deception of the "only one second." Every time you give up, you reinforce addiction without realizing it. Learning to manage these impulses changes your day to day and improve your quality of life. "Bombshell" portrays the true story of the women at Fox News who stood up against the network's powerful CEO, Roger Ailes, exposing his pattern of sexual harassment and the toxic work environment he fostered. The film primarily follows three women: Gretchen Carlson, a former anchor who initiates legal action against Ailes; Megyn Kelly, a star news anchor who grapples with her own past experiences with Ailes while navigating the network's pressures and Donald Trump's attacks; and Kayla Pospisil, a composite character representing the experiences of several young women facing Ailes' predatory behavior as they try to advance their careers. As more women come forward with their stories, a movement begins to take shape within Fox News, challenging the culture of silence and fear that Ailes had cultivated for years. Despite facing immense personal and professional risks, these women band together, their collective courage threatening to bring down one of the most influential figures in media. The film highlights the difficult choices they face, the emotional toll of their experiences, and the far-reaching impact of their actions on the landscape of workplace harassment. How do social networks impact on your emotional state?
 How do social networks impact our emotions?
 Introduction: Social networks have become important of our lives, but 
 To what extent, you have to be aware of the effects of social networks on 
 Our emotions, both positive and negative. 
 Body: one of the ways in which social networks can affect our 
 Emotions is through social comparison. Whenever we enter networks 
 social, we can see photos of people who are happy, successful, beautiful or 
 "better" than us. This comparison with other people can cause 
 Feelings of dissatisfaction, inferiority or sadness.
 Another negative effect of social networks is the effect of loneliness. Even yes 
 We have many followers and friends, most of our interactions are 
 Virtual, and this can have a negative impact on our mental health. A 
 Recent study found that social networks addiction is related to 
 The feelings of loneliness.
 On the other hand, there are some positive effects of social networks. It can be one 
 useful way to relate to people who share similar interests, 
 Even if these people are not in our non -everyday love. This 
 It can be a useful form of support and find comfort in different times. 
 People can use these platforms to tell, compare ideas, 
 exchange tips and support each other.
 In conclusion, social networks have both positive and negative effects on 
 Our emotions. They can be a useful tool to connect with people 
 and tell our stories, but they can also cause loneliness if used in 
 excess. It is important to become aware of the effects of social networks in 
 Our emotions to maintain a healthy balance #Development #Development #Esonal #MOTIVACIONEMOCIONAL
