Fatal familial insomnia is a very rare and invariably fatal autosomal dominant neurodegenerative prion disease caused by a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Hallmarks of the disease include aggressively progressive insomnia, subsequent autonomic disturbances, including tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, and hypertension, cognitive disturbances including deficits in short-term memory and attention, balance problems, and endocrine dysfunction. 

The disease is currently incurable and has an average duration of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. This activity describes the pathophysiology, presentation, and management of fatal familial insomnia and highlights the role of the interprofessional team in the care of affected patients and families.

Fatal familial insomnia (FFI) is a remarkably rare and invariably fatal inherited neurodegenerative prion disease. The mode of inheritance of this disease is autosomal dominant and involves a mutation of the prion protein (PRNP) gene. 

Aggressively progressive insomnia, with subsequent autonomic (tachycardia, hyperhidrosis, hypertension), cognitive (short-term memory and attentional deficits), motor system (balance problems), and endocrine dysfunction are a hallmark of the disease. The disease is currently incurable and has a mean course of 18 months, ultimately leading to death. 

The earliest description of the disease dates back to 1765 with a report of an Italian man with symptoms suggestive of FFI. The disease was formally identified and clinically described in 1986 by Lugaresi E. et al., followed by subsequent studies, further describing its pathophysiology, etiology, and clinical course. 

Genetic prion diseases are very rare. Annually, there are 1 to 1.5 new cases of genetic and non-genetic prion diseases per one million people. Genetic forms of prion disease constitute approximately 10% of the total cases of prion diseases. FFI is exceptionally rare with the disease-causing mutation found in around 50 families worldwide. 

Patients with fatal familial insomnia (FFI) most commonly present between the ages of 20 and 61 years with a mean of 50 years and it affects males and females equally.

A body dysmorphic disorder exists if the excessive concentration on one or more imagined or slight defects in the appearance causes considerable suffering or affects work and/or lifestyle.

#Bodypositivity#Bodydysphormia#Gymbro

Body dysmorphia is a disorder in which a person cannot stop thinking about the defects or failures they perceive in their appearance and that, in turn, for others may seem lower or invisible.

‍ "Although today, in this competitive society and in which the ideal beauty parameters would seem to be those of models (male or female) or Hollywood stars, the truth is that such ideals are unfeasible for the vast majority of mortals and, to a lesser or to a lesser extent, a healthy person mentally knows how to recognize said impossibility and manages to accept herself," explains Daniel Alejandro Fernández (M.N. 41,671), Bachelor of Psychology with psychoanalytic guidance.

 This disorder usually begins in adolescence, when identity is being built and when they belong to a group and interact with peers it becomes relevant.

There’s a difference between being alone and being lonely

The loneliness after divorce hits different than you expect  Everyone prepared me for the divorce itself—the paperwork, the lawyers, the arguments. But no one warned me about the silence that comes after. That first day completely alone in my house, calling my mom over and over just to hear another voice... that's when the real work began. The hardest part isn't the legal stuff or even the fights. It's learning how to be with yourself again. How to fill the quiet. How to rebuild from scratch when everything familiar is gone. But here's what I learned: that rock bottom moment? It's not your end—it's your foundation. Everything you build from here is yours. If you're in that quiet, scary space right now, know that you're not broken. You're not behind. You're exactly where you need to be to start building something beautiful. Your loneliness isn't permanent. Your pain isn't pointless. And your story isn't over. The danger of infinity scroll: Dopamine and digital addiction Have you wondered why it is so difficult to stop scroll in Tiktok or reels? In this video, I explain how the infinite scroll generates a dopamine chute that hooks you without realizing it. Every time you slide your finger, your brain releases dopamine, a substance that makes you feel good and keeps you wanting more and more. A nine-year-old girl was found inside a pit hidden under beer boxes and covered by a concrete lid in a tramandaí commercial establishment on the north coast of Rio Grande do Sul. The rescue occurred on Wednesday morning (26), after the Military Brigade received a complaint. The child had his hands tied and reported being abused by the kidnapper.
The rescue was recorded by the policeman's body camera. During the action, dozens of residents gathered in front of the scene and, by identifying the suspect, Marco Antonio Bocker Jacob, 61, invaded the establishment and lynched him to death. About 40 people participated in the aggression, also destroying the man's store and car. A police officer was hit by a bottle while trying to contain the revolt.

The Civil Police opened an investigation to investigate the participation of other possible involved in the crime and identify those responsible for the suspect's murder. Jacob had an extensive criminal record, including processes for femicide, drug trafficking, theft and bodily injury. On social networks, videos of the girl's rescue and lynching spread quickly, showing the population's revolt in the face of the case.

A woman convinced a criminal who had entered her home with intentions to assault and violate her, to surrender to the police. He offered him food, see a series and then accompanied him to the police station. The 26 -year -old was arrested.

The incident occurred during the early hours of Monday, around 6 in the morning. "It was 6:45 in the morning. I see a man who enters through my window and poured my mouth and tells me:‘ Do not shout because I make you a ballot ’. He started kissing me, he told me‘ Give me a kiss. ’

"I asked him not to do anything to me, I told him that he had children, that he could be his mother. He doubted between taking his pants or listening to me," he recalled.

"I asked him why he did. The woman took advantage of the moment in which the offender slept to send a message on WhatsApp to ask for help from the neighbors. 

"I told him that the police were not going to go, that I could take him to the doctor and make me pass as his mother. I convinced him to change. We went out together, hugged, and we walked a block and a half," said the woman. In that journey were intercepted by the police in May First and Bishop Gelabert, who patrolled the area. What happened to Marilou Vioix?
(If you still don't know your story, this will impact you).
For years, Marilou was a victim of constant harassment by his own university classmates.
The situation became unsustainable ... so much that, one night when leaving a disco, one of them physically assaulted her.
 The blow caused a craniocerebral trauma.
And the university?
He decided to look the other way.
They affirmed that they could not intervene.
But at his graduation ceremony, Marilou made a brave decision:
 The academic band was removed - symbol of its title - as a form of protest.
And he left a letter in each seat, detailing everything he had lived.
He did it in front of everyone.
 From Fateclub we support it and accompany it to a festival with more than 20 attendees,
where he could share his story with respect and freedom.
There, he gave the born publicly (not to bullying),
for his tireless work against bullying.
 Today, his voice has become hope for thousands of people who have been ignored or silenced.

You train, you eat well, you take care of yourself ... and you still don't like what you see in the mirror

That is called body dysmorphia, and more common than you think.

Feeling "small", "fat" or "insufficient" even if you are better than ever ... it is part of something deeper that is not resolved with another series.

Not everything is fixed with muscle. Sometimes, you also have to work your head.

Your progress is worth. Your body deserves respect, even when it is not "perfect."

And you deserve to look with the same eyes with which you admire others.

Comment if you ever felt it. Here is not judged. Here is supported.

Body Dysmorphia (BDD) - a quiet war between us in the mirror 

1️⃣ What is dysmorphia body?
This is a disorder that involves unhealthy, sometimes even obsessive being an absorbed appearance of your own body. The basis of this disorder is not what we look like, but how we assess and perceive us.

As a result, our head begins to find in the body "defects", which we most often see only us! Most often it comes from social or family pressure, unreachable standards of beauty created in the media or perfectionism, which we impose on ourselves.

‍♀️‍♂️‍♂️ Dysmorphia may apply to any person - regardless of the figure, age or sex.

2️⃣ The first symptoms of body dysmorphia
➖ Excessive observing some parts of the body in the mirror.
➖The public places in fear of negative glances.
➖ Dariasly avoiding fitting clothes to cover the figure.

 How to find relief?
The first and most important step is the very awareness of our problem. Without it, we will not start fighting for inner peace and health.

For most people, you will need to work with a psychotherapist who will teach us positive thinking about ourselves with appropriate methods 

A great method for building self -acceptance are trainings focused on learning about your own body - its capabilities, advantages and healthy boundaries

Whenever we talk about the male domestic violence crisis in Australia, someone always brings up stats about queer women not to raise awareness, but to shut the conversation down.

Let’s be clear: violence in queer relationships is real and deserves visibility. But using it only to distract from the epidemic of men’s violence against women is not allyship it’s a tactic.

Over 80% of domestic violence deaths in Australia are committed by men.
This isn’t “whataboutism” it’s a national emergency.

Let’s stop weaponising statistics to protect fragile masculinity, and start protecting lives.

Self love over self everything ✨

When you give things to people or situations that don't "love you back" (i.e., don't reciprocate your efforts or care), it can lead to emotional detachment. This detachment isn't necessarily about becoming cold or uncaring, but rather about protecting yourself by setting boundaries and reducing emotional investment in those unfulfilling dynamics. It's about recognizing when you're giving more than you receive and choosing to prioritize your own well-being. #selflove

One of the biggest lessons I am learning recently is that my story does not need to be validated by other people. There are always going to be people who hate on you for doing literally anything. No matter what you do, you can’t please everybody. And the more I think about it, I don’t want to. I don’t want to have to change my story to fit what other people think it should be. The power in my story is that it is mine and no one can take that away.  So to everyone out there who doesn’t think my story is valid because I don’t fit some stereotype in your mind, open your damn mind. The world isn’t black and white. Educate yourself before you go out and try to bring other people down.  …. My relationship with my phone and social media has changed drastically over the last couple of years, but I still could feel this tiny pull toward my phone, even when I didn’t want to be on it.  

{{TWITTER}} felt too good to be true, so I didn’t let myself get excited about it. 

But wow wow wow this thing has already changed my relationship with tech dramatically 

I’m sure there are tons of benefits to come, but what I’m really enjoying right now is deep, focused, uninterrupted work. I find admin so monotonous so my phone creeps in and gets me off task. apps blocked: email, ig, tiktok 
allowed: Pinterest (one of my biggest sources of inspiration) 

Deep work 
blocked: ig, tt, Pinterest, text messages, email, safari

In my opinion, there are only two situations in which it may be appropriate to comment upon a persons’s body size:

—if they agree to talk about it with you
—if such a conversation may literally save their life and even then, only with the help of a trusted medical and/or mental health professional

Otherwise, I wish we could normalize giving compliments to people that do not directly relate to that person’s body size. You never know how or why that person’s body size has changed—whether they’re larger OR smaller. They could be struggling with an injury, suffering from a debilitating illness (like cancer), or dealing with depression. Why wade into a potential minefield of trauma and pain when a simple “I love your hair!” will suffice?

I also wish we could, in general, just stop talking about diets and losing weight and getting skinny like everyone at the table has somehow agreed that these are totally normal things to talk about with random people who haven’t otherwise demonstrated any interest in such topics. I’m already socially anxious and I feel less inclined to go out with people I don’t know if eating disorders disguised as “diets” are acceptable topics of casual conversation.

I realize not everyone has unhealthy relationships with eating or their bodies, but over 14 million people struggle with disordered eating. There’s a good chance that at least one person at a dinner party, luncheon, or fun run is going through a thing and it doesn’t cost you your soul to just talk about something else or replace “Oh my god you lost so much weight!” with “omg you look amazing!”

“Memory Erasure in Psychiatry” #what Electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) is a highly effective treatment for certain severe mental health conditions, particularly major depressive disorder, treatment-resistant depression, and some forms of psychosis or mania. While it carries stigma due to outdated portrayals, modern ECT is safe, controlled, and done under general anaesthetic. The procedure involves passing a small electric current through the brain to trigger a brief seizure, which can help reset certain brain pathways. It’s typically delivered as a course of treatments over several weeks, not as a one-time fix. For some patients — especially when other treatments haven’t worked — ECT can lead to rapid and significant improvements in mood and functioning. Though it’s not without side effects (like short-term memory loss in some cases), for many people, ECT is a life-changing intervention when other options have failed. #ect #depression #mentalhealth

There’s a powerful, often unspoken link between a messy home and depression. And it’s not about laziness. It’s not about being disorganized. It’s about mental and emotional exhaustion. Behind every cluttered space might be a mind that’s overwhelmed, a heart that’s heavy, or a person trying their best to survive. This isn’t about encouraging perfection or spotless homes. It’s about compassion — for ourselves and others. It’s about recognizing that healing doesn’t always start with deep cleaning — sometimes, it starts with acknowledging the weight of what we’re feeling. If you’re in that place right now — surrounded by mess and shame — know this: you are not broken. You are not lazy. You are not alone. Your worth is not defined by how clean your kitchen is. Start small. One dish. One corner. One deep breath. Celebrate that. Because that is progress. And to those who love someone going through this — offer help, not judgment. Show up, not to clean, but to be there. Sometimes, presence is the most powerful act of care.

The irony is loud, but too often ignored. Right-wing support for ICE exposes a tangle of contradictions that betray the values they claim to uphold. They scream “small government” yet cheer for one of the most bloated, unchecked agencies in existence; empowered to raid homes, detain families without due process, and rip parents from children. They claim to be “pro-life” while staying silent as pregnant women and children die in ICE custody from neglect, lack of medical care, and abuse. They hold up “family values” like a badge of honor while ICE raids have led to thousands of family separations, traumatizing kids who come home to empty houses and unanswered questions. They slap “Support Our Troops” stickers on their trucks while ICE deports veterans who risked their lives in combat. They weaponize “freedom” while applauding indefinite detention without trial. They preach “Christian morality” while turning away refugees, forgetting that Jesus himself was a brown-skinned refugee fleeing state violence. These contradictions aren’t just political, they’re moral. If your values only apply to people who look, pray, or speak like you, then they’re not values. They’re tools of control. It’s time to stop pretending that ICE’s cruelty is about “law and order.” It’s about fear, racism and power. TW: This post discusses body dysmorphia, disordered eating, and past struggles with body image. Do you ever look back at old photos and remember how miserable you felt in your body… …but also remember thinking you were fat? And now, looking back, you can see how thin you really were—how much of you had already disappeared. That’s body dysmorphia. That’s the mindf**k no one talks about. It feels shocking to say but there’s over 40 pounds between the last picture and the video. But here’s what you don’t see in those photos:  The hunger that ran my life  The constant thinking about food  The pressure to stay small  The anxiety over gaining anything  The shame when I couldn’t hold it all together ‍♀️The extreme loneliness and constantly feeling like I was dying inside. Being skinny was never worth the suffering. Life back then wasn’t really life—it was control, obsession, survival. If no one has told you lately:  Your body doesn’t need to be smaller to be worth of love.  Your life doesn’t have to be controlled to be beautiful.  And you are allowed to exist without apology. There’s a huge difference between the video and the pictures. But the biggest one? One thought life was only worth living with the approval of others. The other knows it’s only worth living with the approval of one—herself. #bod#bodydysmorphiar#edrecoveryn#mentalhealthmattersd#bodyimagehealings#disorderedeatingawarenessk#takeupspacel#selfapprovaloverperfectiono#foodfreedomjourneynfidenceovercontrol

** Michael Jackson - “You Are Not Alone” ** 

Whenever I hear "You are not alone", I feel a deep connection to the emotions that Michael Jackson expresses in this beautiful song. The track, which was published on the album * History * in 1995, is a warm message of support and consolation. 

The gentle melodies and Michael's soulful voice remind me that we are all sometimes lonely, but never really alone. The lyrics are so powerful and touching; They offer consolation in difficult times and encourage us to support each other. 

I love how this song conveys the universal message that there is always someone who is there for us - gegal, how challenging life can be. Michael manages to reach people with his music and encourage them in their most difficult moments. 

What does "you are not alone" mean for you? What memories or feelings do this song awake in you? I look forward to your thoughts in the comments!

**"You Are Not Alone"** – a heartfelt anthem of comfort and support! ❤️ Michael Jackson's touching ballad, released in 1995, stands as a powerful testament to the human experience of loneliness and the universal need for connection. With its soothing melody and heartfelt lyrics, "You Are Not Alone" conveys a message of love and reassurance, reminding us that no matter how isolated we may feel, there is always someone who cares. The song was co-written by R. Kelly and showcases MJ’s incredible vocal range, delivering an emotional performance that resonates deeply with listeners. Each note seems to reach out, offering solace to those who may be struggling with heartache, loss, or despair. The way he pours his soul into the lyrics reminds us that vulnerability is a strength, not a weakness. Many fans have shared how this song has been a source of comfort during difficult times in their lives. It encourages us to lean on each other, to seek support, and to remember that we are never truly alone in our struggles. The iconic music video, featuring a beautiful narrative of love and compassion, further emphasizes this message, showcasing the power of human connection. In a world that can often feel overwhelming and isolating, "You Are Not Alone" serves as a gentle reminder that we all have a network of support, whether it's friends, family, or even a kind stranger. It’s a call to reach out, to share our burdens, and to embrace the love that surrounds us. What does "You Are Not Alone" mean to you? How do you find comfort during tough times? Seeing the hate and bullying that most creators get on this app still boggles my mind. Disturbing that people could live in such hatred and negativity. The story of Mikayla Raines particularly affected me. Just  a sweet person trying to do her mission. And yet people can find ugliness and toxic hatred even in such a great mission. Yet they do nothing themselves, except dump hate. I’ve seen beautiful people with amazing stories who inspire me who get that same hate just like I have received. A particular creator could go on a rant - like has happened to me and just spread rumors and lies about you without asking you a single question and having no real information. They just spew hate. My particular hater shall remain nameless I will not give her the attention. But I have an inner strength to see past her ugliness and I will not retaliate or waste my positive energy on someone that toxic. Spreading joy is the highest high  you’ll ever get. You might think you’re getting it with your hatred, feel like you’re in control,  but that energy is pretty shitty compared to love and connectivity. So the challenge is to keep scrolling - if you start there that’s a win. If you can try to do or say something nice for someone else - that feeling is the best. Get help if you need it, but try to change your behavior to positivity or refrain from dumping. And see how YOUR life might change. {{TWITTER}} Raines #bekind #spreadlove #mentalhealth

The same guns are killing us in the U.S. and Mexico.

Last week, a U.S. delegation of gun violence survivors and advocates traveled to Mexico to share their experiences of grief and healing, to stand in solidarity with those impacted by the flood of U.S.-sourced firearms fueling violence across the border, and take to action to stop the deadly flow of U.S. guns across the border.

We met with high-ranking Mexican officials, civil society organizations, and families of the forcibly disappeared to build cross-border strategies for action. At least 70% of crime guns recovered in Mexico come from the United States — a crisis we must confront together.

The delegation shared survivor-led policy solutions to reduce gun violence, hold the U.S. firearms industry accountable, and support Mexico’s efforts to stem gun trafficking.

The week culminated in the Binational Day of Action in Mexico City, where voices from both countries joined together in one clear message: our lives are intertwined — and so is our struggle for justice, peace, and lasting change.

Breast self -exploration: an act of self -love ✨

1️⃣ In front of the mirror: take off your waist clothes up and watch with straight shoulders and hands on your waist. Seeks:
Changes in the form or size.
Dymelos, folds or packages.
Unusual liquids in the nipples.

2️⃣ In motion: Raise your arms and check if you notice any difference in both breasts or the armpits.

3️⃣ Touching: Use the fingertips index, medium and cancel to palpate with circular movements in the direction of the clock needles.
✅ Three pressure levels: soft, medium and firm.
✅ Do not forget to check the armpits, since the breast fabric extends there.

️ Ideal moment:

If menstruals, do it a week after your period.
If not, choose a fixed day every month to keep the habit.
 Remember: Monthly self -exploration can save lives. If you notice something unusual, consult your doctor. Your health is in your hands!

For those who wondered about my "neck hole," it's just a scar from my tracheostomy.  I was 5 months pregnant when I was diagnosed with bone cancer in my jaw.  95% of my jaw was removed and reconstructed with fibula bone. 46% of Gen Z in the UK would become ‘severed’ - choosing to seperate their memories when they are at work and at home, effectively becoming two seperate people. That’s according to a new study by workplace mental health platform Unmind.  Overall, 1 in 3 UK employees would ‘sever’ their work and personal memories, as fears grow about the lack of work-life balance many employees feel they have.  Dr Nick Taylor, CEO and co-founder of Unmind, said, that the findings show how blurred the lines between work and personal life have become. “The challenge for organisations is to create a culture where employees feel comfortable setting boundaries, rather than feeling the need to compartmentalise their work and personal identities,” he said. #severance #worklifebalance #work #working #stressed #severancetvshow #officejob  #corporate #corporatelife

TikTok star Chris O'Donnell, known online as Creeohdee, has died at the age of 31. The fitness influencer passed away on January 11, according to an online obituary. The social media star's death has been ruled as a suicide, according to People. Medical examiners confirmed to the publication that O'Donnell died from a gunshot wound to the head. O'Donnell - who got sober in 2018 and was outspoken about mental health - posted on Instagram in November 2024, sharing a reel of footage from his hiking adventures with the caption: 'I wonder when I leave this earth, when I leave the rat race, when I'm lying in the dirt, if you'd remember my face.' Verbal bullying involves the use of words, language, or verbal aggression to demean, insult, intimidate, or humiliate another person. It can include name-calling, teasing, mocking, spreading rumors, making derogatory comments, or using offensive language. Verbal bullying can be both direct, happening face-to-face, or indirect, such as through gossip or spreading hurtful messages. It's important to note that bullying can manifest in other forms as well, including physical bullying (such as hitting, pushing, or physical intimidation), relational or social bullying (such as excluding, spreading rumors, or manipulating social relationships), and cyberbullying (using electronic devices or online platforms to harass, threaten, or humiliate others). Bullying behavior is harmful and can have severe consequences for the individuals targeted, including emotional distress, decreased self-esteem, anxiety, depression, and even physical injuries. It's crucial to address and prevent bullying by promoting empathy, respect, inclusion, and creating safe environments where individuals feel supported and protected. #Textpledge #Riseup #NoBullying #EndBullying

Three years is not enough!  
A Wichita teen has been sentenced to three years in prison after being found guilty of attacking a 17-year-old girl with acid during a fight. According to KAKE News, 19-year-old Ye'Kira Hollins was sentenced to 34 months after a jury found her guilty of aggravated assault stemming from a May 2024 dispute with the victim, Passionate Turner.

On May 26, 2024, Passion had acid thrown in her face during an altercation in West Wichita. She was taken to the hospital with second-degree burns on her face and neck. There's been no word on what led to the fight. According to KAKE, two other women were involved in the incident and were also charged with aggravated assault. One defendant, 19-year-old Tayronnia West, is scheduled to stand trial on September 19. The third suspect was 16 years old at the time of the incident; her identity has not been released due to her being a minor.

And both are equally horrible to experience.  When we have an anxiety attack it tends to mean our stress response has reached a point of overload, often triggered by prolonged worry or anticipation of a stressful event.   When we have a panic attack it tends to tell us our body's "fight or flight" system has been activated intensely and suddenly, often without an obvious immediate threat.  The primary differences included:   Anxiety attacks build gradually, with a less intense peak. Panic attacks come on abruptly, with a sudden and overwhelming surge of fear.   Anxiety attacks can last for extended periods, even hours. Panic attacks typically peak within minutes and subside relatively quickly. Anxiety attacks are often linked to identifiable stressors or triggers. Panic attacks can occur seemingly out of the blue, though underlying vulnerabilities may exist. Anxiety attacks present with muscle tension, restlessness, and general unease. Panic attacks show more extreme physical signs like chest pain, heart palpitations, and a sense of impending doom. Anxiety attacks are often caused by prolonged stress, or anxiety disorders. Panic attacks can be caused by panic disorder, or extreme stress, and sometimes medical conditions. To Clarify  Panic attacks are a recognised medical condition  'Anxiety attack' is not, but describes real experiences of intense anxiety. Both can be just as debilitating and both require kindness and care.  . . . #anxiety #panicattack #mentalwellbeing #MentalHealthAwareness #studentnurse #MentalHealth

Police Officer Kendall Corder

Milwaukee Police Department, WI

EOW: Sunday, June 29, 2025

Cause: Gunfire

Police Officer Kendall Corder succumbed to gunshot wounds he received when he was ambushed at North 24th Place and West Garfield Avenue in Milwaukee on June 26, 2025.

Around 9:00 p.m., Officer Corder and his partner responded to a domestic violence call with a subject with a gun, which was upgraded to a shots fired call while they were en route to the scene. When they exited their patrol vehicle and approached the alley, they were shot multiple times.

Both officers were transported to Froedtert Hospital. One officer was released on June 28, 2025, after receiving gunshot wounds to the back and foot. Officer Corder remained on life support until passing away from multiple gunshot wounds on June 29, 2025.

The suspect was apprehended the next day and is in custody.

Officer Corder had served with the Milwaukee Police Department for over six years.

I'm always talking about improving sleep and there are a lot of factors that go into it... For example, stopping eating 3-4 hours before bed, limiting blue light and stress, avoiding liquid at least 2 hours before bed, waking up and going to sleep within 30 minutes of the same time every day, using sleep support supplements, and more...

But one of the absolute best tactics for improving sleep is called Resonance Frequency Breathing... 

The goal is to get your breath rate down to 4-7 breaths per minute. 

The best way to accomplish this is to breathe 5 seconds in and 5 seconds out. 

Try this simple tactic and let me know how it works for you in improving your sleep.

☁️ Mindful moment of the day: digital detox.

To achieve a digital detox, follow these three steps:

1. Set a specific time each day to disconnect from screens and digital devices.

2. Create a designated screen-free zone in your home.

3. Plan offline activities that bring you joy to engage in during your digital detox time.

By implementing these steps, you can effectively disconnect from screens, prioritize your well-being, and engage in activities that promote mindfulness and joy.

ADHD, anxiety, and depression often come as a trio, affecting about 30-50% of people with ADHD.  Living with all three can feel overwhelming; ADHD brings challenges with focus and impulsivity, anxiety adds layers of worry and overthinking, and depression can drain motivation and energy. Together, they create a complex web that impacts daily life, relationships, and self-esteem.  Why do these conditions so often occur together? ADHD’s impact on focus, organization, and emotional regulation can make daily life feel unpredictable, leading to chronic stress and, over time, anxiety. Meanwhile, dealing with misunderstandings, stigma, and setbacks can erode self-worth, increasing the risk of depression. There’s also a biological link: ADHD brains regulate dopamine differently, affecting mood, motivation, and the ability to manage stress, which contributes to the development of anxiety and depression. Recognizing this connection can lead to better, more holistic treatment approaches and provide a sense of understanding and validation. If this sounds familiar, our app is like a pocket ADHD coach—helping you understand your brain and build habits that actually stick. 6/27/25 3:45PM PST The Trump administration just announced it will end Temporary Protected Status (TPS) for Haitian immigrants, putting nearly 500,000 people at risk of deportation starting September 2, 2025. TPS is a legal status given to people from countries suffering from war, natural disasters, or other dangerous conditions. It allows them to live and work in the U.S. temporarily without fear of deportation. But now, according to Reuters, the Department of Homeland Security says conditions in Haiti have “improved” — even though large parts of the country are still controlled by gangs, hospitals are overwhelmed, and thousands have been displaced by violence. Most of Port-au-Prince is under gang rule. The U.N. has called the humanitarian crisis in Haiti one of the worst in the Western Hemisphere. Immigration advocates are suing the Trump administration, arguing that ending TPS now is reckless and unjust. If this decision holds, thousands of Haitian families could lose their jobs, their homes, and the only country many of their children have ever known. Some may qualify for other forms of legal status. But many won’t. We’re watching this closely. It’s not just about Haiti — it’s about how the U.S. government treats vulnerable communities, even when they’ve built lives here legally. Follow me on Instagram and Substack for full updates and the full story.

It’s okay to be vulnerable. To feel every emotion, good and bad. To be afraid or confused. To also enjoy happy moments. It’s okay. Cancer sucks. And there is no ONE way to get through this journey.  My heart breaks on a daily basis. So many more people than we realize are struggling or have struggled with cancer. Whether it’s you or a loved one, I’m sorry. And you are not alone. ❤️ Cancer was a reality I never had to face—until now. And I will never be the same. My “life” stopped overnight. Now, I’m bald and basically living at the hospital. Like WHAT?!? My sister and I laugh at the little existential crises we have daily, but they’re real.  When I was first diagnosed, I felt so alone. And I still have moments where I feel a separation from life before. After certain doctor’s appointments—the kind where they overwhelm you with endless side effects and risks—I’ve caught myself looking in the mirror, disassociating. “Is this real?” Anyone relate? But then, I look around and remember: I’m not alone. Someone will smile at me or say something kind, and it brings tears to my eyes. The kindness within this community is overwhelming. We are resilient. We are beautiful. And we hold each other up.     It’s hard to put my feelings into words. I have good days, and I have hard days. Beautiful moments, and traumatic ones. My faith keeps me strong, and I’m grateful for that. It’s not all sunshine and rainbows. I am being strong, but it gets hard too. And if you’re in this fight, I want you to know: You are not alone. We will get through this together. ❤️ #cancersupport #cancerawarness #cancersucks #aml #leukemia

Here are the main rules for the digital detox : 

Rule number one: No more doom scrolling or endless mindless scrolling. I'm taking the challenge of only being on social media when I'm posting because, well, I'm a creator. So, no more endless scrolling for me. 

Rule number two: Delete those social media apps from your phone entirely! I'm talking Instagram, TikTok, LinkedIn, YouTube, Twitter (I refuse to call it X). And don't even try to be sneaky by using the web browser. If you need to look something up, do it the old-school way with good old Google. No shortcuts! 

Rule number three: Reserve the first and last hours of your day for some quality tech-free time. No more waking up to our phones and falling asleep with them. Let's pick up a book instead. 

And last but not least, rule number four: Let's establish 'no tech areas.' For most of us, that means no phone in bed. The bed is for sleeping, remember? 

Now, why am I doing this? Well, as a creator, I realized I was consuming more than creating. And that was messing with my creativity. My work was too influenced by what I was consuming, and I didn't like that one bit. So, I'm going on a social media detox. ‍♂️

If you want to join me on this journey, I'm documenting my two-week detox starting today. And yes, it just had to coincide with my out-of-state trip, but hey, I'll do my best, and I encourage you to do the same. Let's kick those bad tech habits to the curb together.  #DigitalDetox #dopaminedetox #hercontentdiary #contentcreatorjourney

While at first glance, this trend may seem counterintuitive, it offers a refreshing perspective on our hyper-connected lives. Looking for an easy and relaxing way to unwind before bed? ✨ Give these two simple yet powerful exercises a go: 1. Head hang:  When you hang your head in an inverted position, gravity helps align your head and spine, relieving tension in the neck and shoulders.  It can allow blood flow to increase to your brain, which can promote relaxation, making it easier to drift off to sleep. 2. Gentle hair pulling:  As you gently tug on your hair, you stimulate the release of endorphins, the body’s natural pain relievers and mood enhancers.  This can improve headaches, while also serving as a grounding technique to redirect attention from intrusive thoughts or overwhelming emotions. Incorporating these exercises into your nightly routine not only promotes better sleep but also enhances overall wellness.  Personally, I enjoy alternating between these two exercises for 4mins each evening.  What are your thoughts? I'm incredibly proud to share that our team has successfully completed the Ending Violence Against Women & Girls (EVAW/G) project in District Kohat, a journey that spanned two years of hard work, dedication, and positive impact. 

At the closing ceremony, we had the honor of presenting our achievements and reflecting on the progress we’ve made in raising awareness, providing support, and creating safer spaces for women and girls in the community. It was an emotional and inspiring event, made even more special by the presence of Mr. Shafi Ullah Jan, MPA, who graciously appreciated our efforts and presented certificates to our team. 

Mr. Jan also reaffirmed his commitment to fully support these initiatives in the future, ensuring that the fight against gender-based violence continues. His words of encouragement motivate us to keep pushing for change and to empower women and girls in every way possible. 

I’m beyond grateful for the support of my amazing team and for the opportunity to contribute to such an important cause. Together, We Can TKO Domestic Violence

The image before us is more than just a symbol—it represents a battle that too many face behind closed doors. The purple ribbon signifies the fight against domestic violence, while the boxing gloves remind us of the strength required to confront it. Domestic violence is a silent epidemic that can affect anyone, regardless of age, gender, or background.

As a community, it’s time to step into the ring and deliver a TKO to domestic violence. Here’s how we can knock it out together:

	1.	Support Survivors: Listen without judgment and offer resources. Whether it’s a shelter, a counselor, or legal aid, our community must be a safe haven for those affected.
	2.	Raise Awareness: Educate ourselves and others. Domestic violence thrives in silence, but awareness campaigns, workshops, and social media can make a difference.
	3.	Challenge Abusive Behavior: Call out unhealthy behaviors and stand up for those who can’t. It’s not enough to stand by and watch; we must speak out against violence whenever we see it.
	4.	Advocate for Change: Support policies and organizations that prioritize victim safety and abuser accountability. We need stronger laws and community programs that address this issue at its root.
	5.	Empower Everyone: Domestic violence isn’t just a women’s issue; it’s a human issue. Empower men and women alike to understand, prevent, and intervene.

This image speaks of strength, unity, and resilience. Together, we have the power to deliver a knockout blow to domestic violence. Let’s fight for a world where everyone feels safe and supported.

Bullying is a word of English origin, being used to designate a picture of negative attitudes, continuous, repetitive aggressions and with the characteristics of pursuit of the aggressor against the victim. Children and young people victims of psychological and physical aggressions suffer consequences in physical and mental health, such as depression, low self -esteem, drop in school performance, among others.

This isn’t something I speak about often… but there was a time I truly thought I’d ruined everything. I walked away from the person I loved most in the world because I thought I had to. Because I thought love wasn’t enough. Because I didn’t know who I was, or what I needed. And in the months that followed, I made choices that broke me a little more each time. I dated the wrong people. I tolerated things I never should have. I let my heart get bruised in ways I never expected. But somewhere in that mess, I grew. I healed. And just when I stopped looking for anything… life surprised me. He came back. And this time, we chose each other fully.  It wasn’t messy or uncertain. It was real. It was healthy. With clearer eyes, stronger hearts  We got a dog, and now, we’re building a home. A life. A love that feels steady. Safe. Real. We’re creating the kind of love I used to write about in the notes app. So if you’re in the middle of your chaos chapter — hold on. The plot twist might be better than anything you imagined. ❤️ #justanothergirlwithendo #endo #mentalhealth #healing #healyourself #holistichealthandwellness #breakup

1️⃣ in a state of joy, it’s easy for all your subsystems to communicate. They understand that they are part of a larger system that they contribute to and benefit from (love, safety, and belonging)

2️⃣ in chronic states of fear, anxiety, or sadness, your systems lose the capacity to communicate with one another. They start to perceive themselves as alone. In this case, they will work on hyper-drive and get exausted, or lay down and die.

If someone you know through an acute depressive thrust through, it can be difficult to know how you can help. Here are some ways that you can provide effective support that really makes a difference.
At first it is important to be easy. Offer your presence without putting pressure or forcing solutions. Sometimes the best thing you can do is listen and understand without judging.
Recognize the feelings of the depressive person - even if you don't understand them. People in a depression often feel misunderstood or as a burden. Show that your feelings are valid and that you are worth taking it seriously. This alone can have a very relieving effect.
Encourage them carefully to take advantage of professional help if they do not yet have them. Offer to help you find a therapist or doctor or accompany you to appointments if that is desired.
Be patient. Do not expect the situation to change quickly. Depression needs time and every support you offer should be thought in the long term.
By remaining and supportive, you can be a valuable support for a person with depression in acute phases.

⏳ You need to know this about high functioning depression:
• The term itself is not a clinical diagnosis, but a term that has been used online to describe the experience of those who live with depressive symptoms and struggle to function but don’t cease to function.
• This term is pretty useful as many people have a pre-conceived idea that good mental health is all about whether you can still get to work or not. They often feel undeserving of any support because they are not outwardly at rock bottom.
• If you take one thing away from this video, let it be that the best time to start doing the right things for your mental health is the moment you think you could benefit from it. 
• Don’t wait until your mental health prevents you from functioning. That is a much longer and harder journey back.

I took 72 hours off my phone. No social media, no messaging, no scrolling. What surprised me most? I didn’t feel restless. I felt calm. Present. Quiet in a way I hadn’t felt in months. It made me realise how much these devices — even with all their connection — are quietly robbing us of something essential: Our capacity to be here, with our own thoughts, our own bodies, the real world in front of us. Not just robbing us of focus. But of meaningful connection. . To stillness. To real-time human presence. We think we’re plugged in. But we’re often just scattered. This detox didn’t fix everything — but it reminded me of something I’d forgotten: I am not meant to live through a screen #phoneaddict #phoneaddiction #digitaldetox #consciousliving

A bit of screen time is ok isn’t it…?  What’s the worst thing that can happen?  Over time…  Preoccupation with Screens: Spending a lot of time thinking about screen activities even when not using them. Neglecting Responsibilities: Ignoring household chores, work, or school responsibilities to spend more time on screens. Loss of Interest: Losing interest in hobbies, social activities, or other forms of entertainment that were once enjoyable. Withdrawal Symptoms: Feeling restless, anxious, or irritable when unable to use screens. Using Screens to Escape: Using screens to escape from problems or to relieve feelings of helplessness, guilt, or anxiety. Failed Attempts to Cut Back: Trying unsuccessfully to reduce screen time or quit using screens altogether. Continued Use Despite Problems: Using screens despite knowing it causes physical or psychological problems. Lying About Screen Use: Hiding the extent of screen use from family, friends, or therapists. Neglecting Personal Hygiene: Forgetting to shower, change clothes, or eat regularly due to excessive screen use. Relationship Issues: Experiencing conflicts or difficulties in relationships due to excessive screen use. Physical Health Problems: Experiencing headaches, neck pain, or vision problems due to excessive screen use. Social Isolation: Withdrawing from real-life social interactions and preferring online interactions instead. Obviously this is depicting the extreme impacts that can happen over time. And symptoms can vary in severity and may indicate a need for professional help if they significantly impact daily life. But lets set our kids up for success as early as possible. #digitaldetox #screenaddiction #digitaldependencyawareness #technologyaddiction #monitorscreentime

3 Science-Backed Tips to Seriously Improve Your  Sleep  1️⃣ Switch to Red Light  Blue light from your phone or laptop suppresses melatonin—the hormone that signals it’s time to sleep. Switching your iPhone to red light mode or avoiding screens at least an hour before bed can help your body wind down naturally.  Studies from Harvard show blue light is especially disruptive to circadian rhythms. 2️⃣ Watch Your Caffeine Intake  Caffeine has a half-life of 5–7 hours, which means that afternoon latte might still be affecting {{EMAIL}}. And it’s not just coffee—tea, matcha, energy drinks and even dark chocolate can interfere with deep sleep. Research shows caffeine consumed even 6 hours before bed can reduce sleep time by more than an hour. 3️⃣ Try Magnesium for Deeper Rest  Magnesium supports the neurotransmitters that calm your nervous system and helps lower cortisol, your stress hormone. Our Tonic Rest + Recover is formulated to help you fall asleep faster and stay asleep longer. Clinical trials link magnesium supplementation to improved sleep quality and reduced insomnia symptoms. What’s your biggest sleep disruptor right now? Let us know in the comments. #SleepTips #TonicHealth #RedLightSleep #CaffeineCutOff #MagnesiumBenefits

Sleep  Better With Light Exercises   Stretching and meditative movement like yoga before bed can improve the quality of your sleep and the amount you sleep.  Sleep should be a welcome respite, but with our regular routines upended and an almost daily onslaught of anxiety-inducing news, many people are tossing and turning. A study published in June by the journal Sleep Medicine found a 37 percent increase in the rates of clinical insomnia among adults in China from before the peak of the pandemic. Exercise can reduce the amount of time it takes to fall asleep and the amount of time spent awake at night, numerous studies have shown. It also increases sleep time and quality. While experts suggest avoiding vigorous exercise within an hour of bedtime (it raises heart rate, body temperature and adrenaline), stretching and meditative movement like yoga has been found to improve sleep quality. These types of exercises elicit the relaxation response, in which the body experiences a flood of calming hormones and physiological reactions that quiets the nervous system. #sleep #sleepingtips #healthysleep

Struggling to fall asleep even when you’re exhausted?  Your cortisol levels might be running the show. When stress hormones stay high, your body can’t wind down, no matter how cozy your bed is.  Try this: morning sunlight, consistent wake-up times, less scrolling before bed. It’s not a hack. It’s your circadian rhythm finally getting back on track. #bettersleep #sleeptips #cortisol #cortisolbalance #circadianrhythm #hormoneimbalance #wellnesstok #sleeptok

Waking up feeling like a zombie? It’s not your mattress—it’s your sleep cycles! Your body goes through 90-minute sleep episodes all night long, from light sleep to deep sleep to dreaming about wild scenarios. If you wake up in the middle of a deep sleep phase, you’re bound to feel groggy and disoriented. The trick? Time your wake-up at the end of a sleep cycle, when you’re in light sleep (Stage 1 or 2). Aim for 5 or 6 cycles (7.5 or 9 hours) for that refreshed, ready-to-conquer-the-day vibe. Sweet dreams start with smart alarms! ⏰ #bettersleep #SleepTips #scienceexplained #Wellness

May Is Mental Health Awareness Month 

Mental Health is something that is very dear to my heart, having friends who have faced their own struggles and having struggled with mental health for a very long time myself and only now just finding a way to reach out to someone, helping create awareness means a lot to me. I know what it is like to feel like your whole world is falling apart, and like there is no way out because every single day feels like to not much to deal with. No one suffering or being in a hard place deserves to feel like they are not seen or that they are beyond help. Because no matter what it is you are struggling with, you deserve help or advice whatever it is you are in need of. You don’t deserve to feel alone, or unloved, or unwanted, or scared, or anxious, the list of feeling can go on and on, and its so very hard to deal with. You do not have to go through it alone i promise you. If you are struggling please do find a way to reach out, if its a friend or a family member, a trusted adult or a professional, it can make all the difference. Do no suffer in silence. Or if you are worried about someone please check up on them, it may be nothing, but it could also be everything. Having people to support you through tough times is so important. You are not a burden for reaching out. I understand how hard it can be to accept help, especially when you feel unworthy or have never been offered it before, but it’s okay to need help if you are down. You will not be down forever my darling I promise. You are strong and you are loved and you are amazing and i am proud of you. And you deserve to be able to live and love loudly with no fear or worries or pain. Do not give up, you can rise above. So I speak up and I speak out for those who do not have a voice, and for those who lost theirs. I am here for anyone who needs someone to lean on or to talk to !! And if anyone would like some resources i have a few if you’d like. Unfortunately i can’t post every statistic of resource ever but no matter your problem, someone will be there and listen. ❤️

Vampires outside? I’m good.
Spiritual warfare in the streets? Still good.
The end of the world could be brewing out there and I’d be cozy in my house, grounded, protected, safe.

But the second someone says: “Hey… you left your phone outside…”
Suddenly I’m barefoot in the sunlight, negotiating with vampires. 

It’s wild how strong the pull is.

We really are in a toxic, codependent relationship with these phones.
Sleepin’ next to them. Checkin’ them before brushing our teeth.
Low-key goin’ through withdrawals when we can’t find them for 30 seconds.
Like ma’am… breathe. It’s on the couch.  

Sleeping together, waking up together, even shower thoughts together. 
It’s giving codependent situationship 

We don’t realize how emotionally attached we are to these little devices.
They’ve become extensions of us—our connection to the world, our validation, our business, our memories, our coping mechanisms.
We reach for them without thinking. Scroll without seeing. Panic when they’re out of reach.
It’s not just a habit anymore.
It’s a bond.

And in some ways, it mimics a toxic relationship:
You know you should take space, but you can’t.
You know it’s draining you, but the silence feels worse.
You keep going back… even when it hurts your peace.

But at least I’m not alone, right? 
Let’s be honest—what’s the longest you’ve gone without your phone lately?
And did it feel like freedom or straight-up withdrawal?

Magnesium for better sleep
In 19 clinical trials, 320–729 mg at bedtime helped people fall asleep about 17 minutes faster and sleep a bit longer. More than 350 mg elemental magnesium can loosen your bowels and, if you have kidney issues, build up in the blood. (PMID 33865376)
 Omega-3 fish oil for inflammation
At least 1 g of EPA + DHA daily for three months or more lowered blood markers like CRP, IL-6 and TNF-α. High doses can thin the blood, so talk with your clinician if you take aspirin, warfarin or other anticoagulants. (PMID 17335973)
️ Vitamin D for immune support
A review of 45 studies found that daily or weekly vitamin D cut respiratory-infection risk by up to 50 percent in people who were deficient to start. Aim for a blood level above 30 ng/mL; most adults need 600–2 000 IU a day, more if a lab test shows a shortfall. (PMID 32353972)
 Ashwagandha for stress & cortisol
In a 60-day trial, 300 mg of standardized root extract twice daily lowered morning cortisol by 28 percent and eased anxiety. Effective range: 300–600 mg per day for 8–12 weeks. Buy from reputable brands—potency varies. (PMID 23439798)
 Creatine for brain and muscle
Five grams a day replenishes cellular energy. Meta-analyses show roughly 10 percent more strength and about 1 kg of extra lean mass when combined with resistance training. Small studies also report quicker thinking after sleep loss. Safe for healthy kidneys. (PMID 14561278)
Quick safety checklist
1️⃣ Stick to research-supported doses—more isn’t always better.
2️⃣ Look for NSF, USP, or Informed-Sport seals to dodge contaminants.
3️⃣ If you’re pregnant, have chronic illness, or take prescription meds, get professional guidance first.
